animal.description:
Huey was owned by a ranch hand who left the ranch and left Huey behind. When no one else at the ranch paid him much attention, Huey went wandering. For 4 months, he wandered a country neighborhood alone, following families on their walks with their dogs and playing with dogs along their fence lines, but was unwilling to let anyone catch him. He just didn't trust humans enough to let them come close.
 He spent both excruciatingly hot and freezing cold days laying out in the elements, in plain sight, but uncatchable. Animal control tried for 3 months. Neighbors tried to entice him into yards. The kind neighbors kept him fed, but he still wouldn't trust anyone. 
Finally a trapper stepped in and set a trap for him. A couple of days later, while checking the trap, the trapper was startled to look up and see him watching her. She watched him as he ambled by the trap location and down the street. She followed from a distance and found he had wandered into a neighbors fenced yard to play with her dog. A closed gate, snare, a can of vienna sausage snacks and an hour later, and he was on his way to a new life. 
At first, he flinched when touched, having forgotten the sensation. But with time and love he has tuned into a big, lovable baby who adores attention. He has no concept of his size and would prefer to be a lap dog. He is fairly low energy and is happy napping on the couch or outside in the sun. He walks well on a leash, but has a bit of fear about getting into the car that he is working on. He enjoys a hike at the park, but doesn't need a lot of high energy exercise to be happy. 
He loves toys, but mostly just carrying them around and trying to bury them in the yard. 
He enjoys other dogs, especially smaller ones. He might take a bit of an adjustment period with other large dogs, but he has become friends with every dog he has met eventually. 
He mostly sleeps on a dog bed, but once in awhile climbs up into bed to cuddle. He will chew on things you leave on the floor if you're not careful, but he's not a destructive chewer generally and does well left out at home unsupervised. 
He is not a fan of a kennel, but can be kenneled if necessary. 
Huey just needs love and a lifetime supply of dog chow to be happy. He'll even give you the biggest butt wiggles you have ever seen when you walk through the door. What more could a human ask for?

animal.description:
Odie was found living on the streets in a neighborhood where loose dogs unfortunately go largely unnoticed. But when a good samaritan realized he was never going to  a home and sleeping on the side of a road, she called us to trap him. He would sit quietly on the side of a busy road as people passed him by, until they looked his way. As soon as someone seemed to notice him, he would take off in fear. Our team set a trap for him and within a couple of days, some hot rotisserie chicken coaxed him into the trap and he was suddenly off the streets.
It only took a few days and some serious loving before it was clear that someone had loved him in his life before. Odie was already house-trained, loved snuggles and kids, and could charm the pants off of anyone. But his family has not been found. 
After a few months in his foster home. the unthinkable happened. While his foster mom was away, something sparked a fight among his foster brothers. While all of the dogs were injured, Odie took the brunt of it. He nearly didn't make it. It has taken thousands of dollars, 4 surgeries, and 2 long months for Odie to recover and once again become the silly, happy guy we know. Through all of the ordeal, Odie has maintained his usual sunny attitude and never felt sorry for himself. One of his ears has moved high on his head and he got a bit of an unneeded face lift. He is now back to taking walks and living his best life and is once again looking for a new spot to call forever.

From Odie's foster mom:
It is said that when you adopt a dog, they’re a part of your world, but to them, you’re their whole world. This dog, Odie, is so beautiful, so wonderful, so special, that he will be someone’s whole heart. It is his fate. And he deserves it.  He has been an absolute joy to foster. Zero accidents, zero destruction. He’s a complete looney who can self entertain. He hugs like it’s the last hug you’ll ever have or need. When first leashed, he’ll send you flying down a set of stairs at Mach 3. You’ll want to work on that one. He’s eager to learn and please. He’ll follow you wherever you go, forever.  He’s 45-47lb and is two-ish yrs old. World’s softest fur; low shedder. He gets along well with other dogs, but does appreciate animals who give him personal space. Is fun at the dog park. Want a sensitive, sweet, party animal— one who has the potential for service work or being a young child’s soulmate — want someone this amazing in your life?  He’s looking for you, too!

animal.description:
Everyone needs a big lover boy Kail in their life! When you walk into foster moms house, you will be greeted by a big wiggly boy holding his latest favorite toy (usually a de-stuffed dog toy thats WAY too small for him). He will prance around the house until youre settled and then sit patiently RIGHT in front of you until you pet him. Take too long? Get ready for him to, gingerly, give you his paw just as a reminder that he is right there (just in case you cant see him). Kail is just like other 75lb dogs - he thinks his rightful place is in your lap. Kail is well mannered though and knows to wait for permission until he can come up on the couch. If he doesnt have permission, he will begrudgingly lay at your feet or on a near by dog bed. If he can come up, he will lay right next to you with at least a paw on your lap. Kails love of humans doesnt stop at adults. He loves any kids he meets and is so incredibly gentle. However, when he plays he doesnt know where his body is. Kail (and young kids) would need more training to make sure hes not knocking anyone over.


When you are ready to play, he loves to play fetch or tug-of-war with his big rope. Ready for an adventure? Kails in too! He LOVES to go on runs with his foster family, just not every day and slower than 9-minute miles please. Kail also loves to hike and is working on his trail manners. He is also treadmill trained but would much rather be outside on walks and runs with his family for his exercise! Kails also excited to try his hand at cross country skiing once there is enough snow because he LOVES the snow so why not combine two of his favorite things?!? You will know when hes happy and ready to go because he gets on his racer Kail ears.

Kail lives with his foster sister, Luna, and loves her! However, he appreciates slow introductions and no face-to-face introductions as the first hello. Kail tends to like confident dogs (no matter their size!), however some smaller dogs might not like when he tries to play. Hes worked SO hard on his dog-friendliness and would love a forever home that will continue to advocate for him, be his alpha dog, and continue to work with him!

Kail already knows all of his basic commands - sit, down, shake, and wait. He is currently working on spot and come! He is also leashed trained so no pulling here! Kail will need continued practice to keep his skills sharp!


Kails story is still waiting to be written by his forever family! His first decided they didnt have time for him anymore. At only 3.5 years old, will you give this lover boy a chance and let him be a part of your family forever?
 


 

Kail playing: https://youtu.be/q9PbozJvkcE

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration

animal.description:
Here is more about Jake!

3-years-old, 50-pounds

Jake is looking for a home with a fenced-yard – he is not a candidate for an invisible fence. tie-out, or dog park. He is also looking for home without shared walls (no apartments or townhomes). 

Jake will need consistent training and patience to help him with his uncertainty around new humans. He is a pro at supporting social distancing and takes multiple visits (with lots of high value treats) to warm up to someone. Once he is comfortable with someone, his personality comes through and he loves ear scratches, belly rubs and playing with his toys. 

He will also need a home familiar with the Aussie breed. He has all the traits that have been bred into his Aussie background. A home committed to nurturing his busy Aussie lifestyle, mentally and physically will be important. If you give Jake an inch, he will run a mile – his forever home will need to ensure he knows that he does not run the house. 

Jake needs a kid-free and cat-free home but would do alright with another dog in the home provided there are slow, controlled introductions and ample time for both dogs to decompress once Jake is in his forever home. Jake likes to play with other dogs but can be a little pushy around toys when he wants them. 

Jake is looking for a home where he will be loved, provided with consistent training, and given ample opportunities to get his Aussie energy out!





His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

Interested in adopting and/or learning more? Visit http://pethavenmn.org/adopt/

animal.description:
Born December 2018, Klondike is a 95-pound teen-pup that came to us from a shelter. He probably lived in a home at one time because he is potty trained and will sleep in a crate with no fuss. This teenager is learning doggy manners. With exercise, mental stimulation (enrichment), and appropriate chewing toys like a Nylabone, Klondike is learning what is acceptable.  He enjoys playing with a tennis ball to release energy before a walk. This seems to really soothe him. 

He needs to continue fear-free dog training to help build confidence. New environments and experiences cause anxiety so baby steps for this pup.  He may benefit from having a young female companion but no small pets of any kind. He thrives with structure and enjoys affection.  

**Northern Breed & Force-Free Dog Training Experience Required** 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering Klondike, please contact CHAAMP at CHAAMPapplication@gmail.com for an application. You may also complete an application online thru our web site, www.CHAAMP.org

CHAAMP accepts applications ONLY from Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Virginia, West Virginia, and Washington DC. The information on your application will help CHAAMP determine which of our dogs is a good match for you and your family, based upon your lifestyle, other pets, etc. A home visit is required prior to all adoptions. Many of our dogs are fostered in private homes and cannot be visited until you have been approved for adoption. 

ADOPTION FEE is $275.00

animal.description:
Please note following information of what Lilly and her sister Leah need in an adoptive family:

SINCE LEAH AND LlLLY HAVE BEEN TOGETHER SINCE THEY WERE BORN, NOW ARE JUST OVER ONE YEAR OLD, IT WOULD BE DIFFICULT TO SEPARATE THEM. SO WE ARE LOOKING FOR A HOME WHERE THEY CAN BE ADOPTED TOGETHER.  

Lilly will need a home where the family is patient with her and willing to give her the time she needs to adapt and feel comfortable. It takes her a while to warm up to people and to trust them so it won’t be an immediate or overnight connection. The family that adopts her should be willing to take it slow with her and expect to wait several weeks to months until she shows that she is learning to trust.  Lilly will bond more closely to women, so a relationship with a female could develop fairly quickly, but it will take her a longer time to adjust to any males in the house. When people they know come to visit her foster home, Lilly is friendly with those she knows, but uncomfortable with strangers, especially males. 
 
The same can be said for Leah, but Leah is less social than Lilly. Leah is more fearful and sometimes will growl when she is unsure or uncomfortable. She will need a longer period of time to adjust to a home. People that adopt Leah need to understand that she is timid and fearful of new  situations and they will have to be willing to be patient over an extended period of time, not pushing or trying to rush her, but allowing her to go at her own pace.

Young children will be too stressful for the girls. They both will need homes where people are experienced with dogs and are willing to take the time to win their trust. This is going to be a long process and not an immediate bonding.  

The girls are used to running freely in the yard so a fenced in yard is needed.  Lilly and Leah love to walk and go for daily long walks.  They also meet people along the way, which helps with socialization. They are comfortable in a crate can be crated and for up to five hours daily.  If someone worked away from home, that would be OK, but they could not for be crated for a full work-day.

Update 6/13/2020. Lilly and Leah are sisters who had a difficult start in life. They were found under an abandoned building and this is the message 
that Furry Friends Network received from the shelter that rescued them. 

"They were pulled from under an outbuilding and had not been handled until yesterday. But they are curious little tykes, probably about 8 weeks old. I'm so glad that we got them out from under that building. Poor little things would have died from worms! They were pulled out of some of the worst circumstances ever, but they are now safe. They would not have lived had we not got them from under the outbuilding and treated and cared for them." 

Now Lilly is a 8-9-month old puppy weighing about 22 pounds, a very pretty girl with beautiful white fur and black and brown markings. It takes Lilly some time to get used to new people. Through the first couple of months of her life, she had no interaction with humans, and she also was abandoned by her mother, so she did not have a positive start in life. Now she needs time to feel comfortable with her humans and to trust them. She is affectionate and friendly with her foster mom, a relationship that was built through several months. Thinking that she and her sister, Leah, would be more comfortable if adopted together, these two girls were placed in an adoptive home with each other, but Lilly, who is somewhat more friendly than Leah, seemed to become more fearful and the situation for both girls was not what we had expected. Lilly is very dog friendly though, and if she lived with a well-adjusted and friendly other dog, that could have a more positive impact on her. She is very sweet and gentle, just needs a home where she will be accepted and understood, a home filled with patience and kindness. Once her trust is won, the relationship with her humans will be intense and never ending.  

Adoption application, home visit and adoption fee required. If you would like to apply for adoption, please complete the online application at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under ADOPT tab. Please also read our Core Values prior to applying. Contact generalinfo@furryfriendsnetwork.com for questions or if issues are encountered with the adoption application or general adoption process.

Foster Homes are desperately needed in order to help more animals like this one. Please consider opening your heart and home to a homeless animal. To find out more about becoming a Foster Parent, see our website at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under VOLUNTEER tab.

As part of our adoption agreement, we require that you and your adopted canine attend a minimum of one group basic obedience course within 4 months of adoption. If adopting a puppy under 4 months old, we also require a group puppy socialization course be started immediately upon adoption.

In addition, we require that puppies under 6 months of age will not be alone for more than 4 hours at a time in an 8 hour workday. We highly encourage working families to consider older puppies and adult dogs, but if your heart is set on a puppy, please consider doggie daycare.

animal.description:
Hi there, I’m glad to see you checking out my page! I’m Cesar Ranger and it’s great to meet you. I’m looking for a new family to call my own! Could it be you?

Here’s my stats:
Possible Breed:  Lhasa Apso
Gender:  Male
Colors:  Black and white
Age:  4 years

Now for the good stuff!-

I am so ready for a forever home!  I get excited when my foster mom comes home and I want to get excited when my forever mom or dad come home!

I'm a big guy but oh so gentle.  In every thing I do, I'm gentle.  I walk slowly, take treats where you almost don't know I've taken it, and I love to sleep all curled up.

I may be blind but that doesn't stop me from getting around and exploring my environment.  I can go outside on my own and then find my way back in.  I find the water with no problems too.  I wasn't always blind so that has probably helped.  My nose really helps me especially when it comes to finding food.

I'm a quiet kind of guy where you almost don't know I'm around.  I don't make a fuss about anything.  Well, if I'm behind a gate and I want to get out, I will be persistent and let you know in an quiet way but  you will know.  

I'll make someone a wonderful friend.  Are you the one for me?

PS. I've had ALL my vetting, and oh boy, it was a lot. Here's what I had done..
Distemper/Parvo shots - TWICE (Foster Mom said we have to have two so that we are protected from these horrible viruses. One doesn't cut it.)
Bordetella shots - ALSO TWICE. 
Spay/Neuter, of course.
A fecal exam so I don't have any bad worms.
A heartworm test.
BLOODWORK to make sure my liver and kidneys are working well, because you know, we doggies often have issues in the liver and kidneys.
A DENTAL exam AND cleaning if I needed it- yep, all my toofies are checked so they can be in tip top shape
See, that's a LOT. Ask your vet - that's a LOT.

You can apply to adopt this adorable little fluff at www.shihtzu-rescue.com.  This adorable little fluff has been spayed or neutered, is up to date on all vaccinations and heartworm negative.

animal.description:
ADOPTION FEE: $300WEBSITE: www.huskypackrescue.com

Name: AKIRA
Gender: FEMALE
Age: 1 and half years old
Size/Weight: 45 lbs
Breed: Husky/German Shepherd
Energy Level: Medium
Good w/cats? YES
Good w/dogs?: YES
Good w/children: YES, older kids would be best
Personality: Akira is a one and half year old husky/shepherd mix girl that is good with small dogs and cats. She needs someone with time and patience to help her understand that people just want to love her.
Her adopter must be very local as it will take multiple visits and time for her to get comfortable before an official adoption can happen. She must have at least one other dog to play with as she is very dog social and comfortable. A six foot privacy fence is a must with her. She needs a person that understands she just prefers to not be pet. She will play/juke/talk/hike with someone, but cuddling is just not her thing. Akira doesn't have an ounce of aggression in her as she is more the flight in fright risk. She is such a unique and beautiful girl with great personality just in her own way.

______________________________________________________________________________
HEALTH: All Husky Pack Rescue dogs are current on vaccines, dewormed, microchipped, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption.
APPLICATION PROCESS:

Complete Adoption Application at http://www.huskypackrescue.com/adoption-application

What we are looking for on the application:

All pets must be spayed or neutered

All dogs must be on Heartworm preventative

Ability to exercise your Husky daily

Adoptions can NOT be given as gifts

Demonstrated willingness to take care of your new dog for its lifetime

Ability to pay our adoption fee - cash, check, money order or PayPal

Veterinarian reference is highly preferred

We will review your application and respond within 7 days.
If your application is approved we will set up a time for you to meet your chosen dog.
Even though your adoption application may specify a particular dog, the result of a successful application only means you are approved to adopt through HPR, not that you are approved to adopt that particular dog.
If the potential adopter causes a delay in the adoption after they are approved, we CAN NOT guarantee the dog you are interested will still be available when you are ready, especially if there are other applicants interested in the same dog.
We do not adopt on a first come, first serve basis; we choose the best application to match the needs of each of our dogs.
We do not have a shelter facility nor do we have any set open/closed hours. We are a foster based program with all our dogs living with a foster family.
A home visit is required prior to every adoption.

CONTACTS:
General Questions,Comments, Donations: info.huskypackrescue@gmail.com
Interested in Fostering or Volunteering: info.huskypackrescue@gmail.com

NOTE: Bella is currently being fostered at Main Street Pet Resort. Please email fortleavenworthstrayfacility@gmail.com for an adoption application and/or call MSPR for more information: (816) 858-7387.

Belini (aka Bella) is estimated to be about 6 or so years old. She was adopted from another organization about a year before she was relinquished to us, which was about a year ago. (That organization guessed her to be 3-4 years old at the time.) Her former family brought her in to us just before the holidays in 2019 to help her find a better match.

Bella is a sweet dog, a very friendly girl. She does her chores quickly when let out, is happy to run around the yard awhile and then kennels up beautifully. Seems to be pretty happy to please if you have a treat. She seems a little deaf if you don't have a treat, ha!

She does pull on the leash and weighs about 80 pounds, so she'll need someone who can handle her and can give her regular exercise.

She went for a trial adoption visit to a home that had a dog and cats. She was wonderful WONDERFUL with the humans, children included, but did not do well with the resident dog and cats. Thus, she might do best in a home as the only pet or with another dog she "chooses."

Call 913-684-4939 or email fortleavenworthstrayfacility@gmail.com.

Featured as the Pet of the Week in the Jan. 2, 2020, issue, as well as the April 30, 2020, online issue, of the Fort Leavenworth Lamp.

Bella has been waiting patiently for the right family to find her, but it has been A YEAR (yes, a full year!) since she came into our care and she really should be in a home instead of in limbo!

Featured as the Pet of the Week in the Jan. 2, 2020; April 30, 2020; and Jan. 21, 2021, issues of the Fort Leavenworth Lamp.

ADOPTION APPLICATION:
Please email us for an adoption application form or drop by the facility to fill one out. Thanks! Email fortleavenworthstrayfacility@gmail.com or lampphotog@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Meet Athena! This senior girl has quite the story. 

This sweet angel was picked up as a lost dog in mid-October 2019. She was adopted from us shortly after that, but was then picked stray again November 2019. She was never redeemed. She was heartworm positive and we wanted to get her treated, so she went into foster care in February 2020. What should have been a 3 month stay in foster care has turned into 8 months because we found out almost as soon as she went into the foster home that she is a seizure patient. 

She is some type of hound mix , so she lives by her nose. She walks very well on a leash but walks tend to be slow because she is constantly looking for food (earthworms and bugs are her favorites).  Athena is also known to resource guard not only food, but also the couch. She will snarl if you touch her while she is on the couch. She thrives on the attention she gets from her favorite humans. Athena is funny … she is so clumsy and bouncy as she jumps around the kitchen for food (because true to her breed, it is all she thinks about). Athena “mothers” her foster parents’ dogs … she just loves to be near them.

Small children are not recommended because of the resource guarding and she just doesn't know her size. Athena loves people. She is guesstimated to be almost 8 years old. She has finished her heartworm treatment and is due for her heartworm test to confirm she is negative in December 2020. Athena does suffer from seizures but with her three times a day medication, her seizures have decreased in frequency. If medicating as directed, the frequency has dropped to about 1 seizure every 2 months. The medication costs approximately $30.00 per month. 

We don’t know what she went through in her life, but we do not think car rides were a pleasant experience for her. Athena is scared to get in any vehicle … even treats don't always help. Adopter needs to be able to lift her 50 lbs. body in case she protests getting in.

animal.description:
Emmett was found outside a rural home in SE Missouri on December 8, 2018. He was bloody, bony, and shivering with cold and pain, yet he was calm and gentle as I got him into my car and took him home. Emmett is now about 5-7 years old, 70 pounds, neutered, UTD on vax, dewormed, and microchipped. He tested a “strong” positive for heartworms on 1/2/19 and was still a “weak” positive on 10/1/19 after months of slow kill treatment with doxycycline and Advantage Multi.

Emmett loves every person he meets! He’s very strong and plays rough, so he probably shouldn’t be in a home with small children. He doesn’t get along with most dogs and chases cats, so Emmett definitely needs to be the only companion animal in the home. Emmett has unrestricted access to a fenced yard and always uses the doggy door to potty outside. He doesn’t climb fences or dig holes. He’s crate trained and walks well on a leash. Emmett knows to sit before he gets fed and before exiting the door for walks. He makes the silliest grunting and whining sounds to get my attention. He has a moderate energy level and plays with his toys by tossing them in the air and then pouncing on them. Emmett has a lot of love to give and really needs a home of his own.

If you would like to be considered for adoption, please complete the adoption questionnaire on our website www.heartsofgoldpitrescue.com.  

* 6 years old
* Only been in a crate to travel
* Uses doggy door
* Very, very dog selective. Need to be only dog.

animal.description:
SPECIAL NEEDS
Tiny 16 year old Goosie was abandoned on the side of the road by her family who no longer wanted her, and now a happy new life has sprouted.  Goosie is looking for a calm, stable home where she can settle into a routine, and enjoy her golden years with someone who is home all or most of the time, and with special needs dog experience with ability to make her their priority. She should be the only dog in the home as she guards her food an may lash out at other dogs but she very much enjoys the company of cats. She is house trained but may have accidents due to her age and medications.  Her age-related health challenges have improved through prescription diet, supplements and medications (arthritis, early stage renal disease, liver imbalance, tooth tartar, heart murmur) - she remains a feisty girl despite deafness, blindness in the left and partial sight in the right eye. She enjoys short 10-20 minute walks but due to limited mobility needs to be carried for curbs, stairs and uneven terrain as she may stumble and fall. She loves cuddling and napping with her people when it suits her, playing with her toys, and her treats! Riding in a crate or carrier in the car is best and helps to calm her during short drives (which she finds stressful).  If you think you could be a great fit for Goosie, please e-mail us for more information! therealbark@gmail.com

animal.description:
Billy! 
Sweet Sweet Billy... this fella is as gentle and calm and quiet as they come. He is shy and takes time to warm up but the reward is definitely worth the wait! Billy came to Save A Pet from animal control in Macon. He was the very last dog to leave before a temporary closing and was set to be euthanized if we did not save him. We knew IMMEDIATELY that Billy was so worth saving. He was so sweet but very guarded. It took awhile for his personality to show. Billy is quiet and extremely observant. We often catch him ""peeking"" in from the outside of his kennel watching us work. He will come to the front of his kennel and watch everything going on. He prefers to have his bowl outside with him and you can hear him pick it up to eat outside! He is funny to watch!
Billy enjoys the company of other dogs and would probably do best with a confident companion. He sure does love his Sadie May! She is his best friend and they play together every day. Sadie has really helped Billy come out of his shell!
Billy is 3.5 years old and weighs about 60 pounds. He is very handsome and is such a good boy!!

We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!12/30/2019 Ranch evaluation. Maxx's is relaxing he will nip at peoples legs when they come in, especially men. He is somewhat handshy. Today for the first time we saw him actually playing with one of the younger dogs which was very cool to see :)Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
For up-to-date info like events, closings, new animals, success stories please LIKE Manchester Animal Shelter on Facebook!

Miss Fiona is finally available for adoption! This beautiful girl is a 46 pound, 6-year-old, pocket pit looking for her forever home. She came to us as a stray in the worst shape. Skinny, malnourished, and mangey, and that was only the beginning. We believe she was dumped in Manchester and was probably fending for herself for quite some time. This petite gal is nothing short of a warrior, a fighter, a survivor!

Once she was in our care, Fiona started her road to recovery. It took over a year until she was finally healthy and strong. Finding the right diet and medications &learning to trust people again. Now she goes on outings where she ventures to public places and continues to amaze us with the progress, she makes each time! She was so stubborn at first when we initially started training, and now she thoroughly enjoys it. She is highly intelligent, and she knows it! Her circle of friends continues to grow, and we couldn’t be prouder!

Fiona loves to be out in the yard. She sunbathes and rolls around on her back, legs flailing in the air, just soaking up her happy place. She will stalk birds and squirrels and enjoys sounding the alarm, so everyone knows there is a person at the door. Fiona also does well in the car. Whatever gets her out of the shelter is good enough for her! She is recently being fostered with one of her favorite volunteers. We receive an outstanding report every time we check-in. She does well in a home, no accidents, and doesn’t seem too upset being there alone. She makes herself at home, slinking up on the couch and watching soap operas while her foster dad is at work. That’s the life according to Miss Fi!

Introductions with this beauty will need to go slow to ensure a smooth transition. Once she warms up and knows she can trust you, you are a friend for life. It’s an honor to be her friend. The way she was treated by previous humans, could have left her aggressive and lost. That’s the power of a pit bull though. They are such exquisite creatures and we should all take a page out of their book. 

Fiona needs to be the only pet in the home. No young kids in the home either. It may be possible for her to live with older, mature, teenagers. Otherwise, Fiona is content being your one and only!

So, what do you think? Are you ready to meet Fiona? Please contact canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org to start the ball rolling!


Adoption fee is based on age:
Puppies 8 weeks to 7 months are $400
Dogs 8 months to 7 years are $325
Senior dogs over 8 years are $125
Senior for Seniors (Seniors 65+ adopting over 7 years): $75

All adoptable dogs are spayed and neutered, have age and time appropriate vaccines, microchipped and heartworm tested. Other medical care provided might include treatments for fleas, ear mites, dental work or infections or other medical conditions. Additional vaccinations and medical care (including puppies Rabies shots if adopted at under 12 weeks of age) will be the responsibility of the adopter.

If you have questions you can call our office at 603.628.3544. To complete out an adoption application come to 490 Dunbarton Rd in Manchester, NH, during the shelters open hours. 
We do not do same day adoptions 

Adoption hours: 
Saturday: 10-4
Sunday: 12-3
Monday and Friday: 12-4
Tuesday and Thursday: 12-7pm
Closed on Wednesday
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: As with all of our dogs, we strongly recommend obedience classes for new owner and dog to create a life-long bond with the adopted dog based on trust, respect, and rewarding training experiences. Our shelter dogs are strays and we observe and assess their behavior at the shelter which may be somewhat different in a home environment.

animal.description:
Olivia has been looking for a forever home for over a year now! Her estimated DOB is 4/2014. She is gentle, calm, loves to cuddle, and enjoys car rides. She will bond strongly to her family and would love to go everywhere with them. While she is calm and gentle, she is a large dog, weighing 106 pounds and can be stubborn so she needs a strong guiding hand. Olivia likes some dogs (prefers easy going males), but would be fantastic as an only dog. She should not be with cats or small dogs. This girl is uncomfortable around small children, so an adult only home or a home with older children (13 years+) is a must. Olivia is housebroken. She does need to be on a special diet for her urinary health. She does fantastic on this food and it keeps her urinary tract healthy and free of crystals. Since she does have to be kept on this prescription food, FOPAS is offering a permanent foster situation for Olivia. You provide a safe, loving home and FOPAS provides food and medical care for Olivia. 

If you are interested in Olivia, fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

She had 8 puppies on January 4, 2019.  she has since been spayed and is current on her shots.  Dixie still acts very much like a puppy herself.  She has a lot of energy and loves to run in her fenced yard.  She just loves attention and can be very affectionate.  Dixie is fine with women but picks the men she likes.  She does not care for young, active children.  The best home for Dixie would be one as an ONLY pet, a quiet home with a fenced yard.  She will need someone with dog experience that will work with her on her insecurities.  Dixie is just so happy to see people that she trusts.  We are hoping someone will give her the home that she deserves.

animal.description:
Hi all!!! It’s Bubbles again. My forever humans still haven’t found me and I really need your help to find them. I am a grown up dog at 5 years old so that means I know where to do my business and I already trained the humans how to give me treats for good boy behavior. I stay off counters and furniture (although sometimes I like to borrow the fluffy blanket off the couch). I am kennel trained and I get along with doggies of all sizes. Also I get along really well with all humans (including the shrunken kind). I am laid back, mild mannered, and low energy. Unfortunately no dog is perfect. I am not very good with the scratchy creatures my foster mom refers to as “cats” but I can behave around a barn scratchy. Also I have this condition called ADOST (attention deficit oh squeaky toy). This means my forever humans need to have an abundance of squeaky toys available at all times. Despite this crazy condition, I am a very good boy who knows how to take care of my squeaky toys so they don’t spontaneously explode. Although sometimes my toys get to talking to much and lose their voice. Other than that I am as close to perfect as perfect gets. I know not everyone can adopt right now so if you don’t mind sharing me out, I’ll make sure to pay it forward by being an excellent advocate for my breed.
Thanks for reading and I can’t wait to meet my forever family!

We are recommending that Bell find a home where she will be an only dog. 













































when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; SCPR believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.doitforthedogs.com. We are the Second Chance Pet Rescue in Grove, OK. 918-786-7630. animal.description:
Hey everyone!  I’m Maggie, a bulldog/boxer mix.  The best of both worlds here:  the athleticism of a boxer with the wrinkles and love of a bulldog! 

I have been with IBR for about a month now and am starting to open up a bit more.  It takes a long time for me to adjust to new places, so I am grateful my foster parents took it really slow with me.  This meant that they let me have my own space for a few days to decompress and only my foster mom came in and out so I didn’t get too overwhelmed, and because sometimes men freak me out.  A few days later I met my foster dad and I actually really liked him, too!  When new people come around my foster mom tells them to allow me to come to them on my own time rather than approach me because sometimes it makes me feel scared.  I tend to attach to one person who makes me feel confident.  I need someone who is patient and will allow me to open up on my own terms because I promise if I can move slow with introductions and adjusting I am such a sweet girl that gives cute big smiles!  

There are other dogs in the house, but I do not like them at all.  My foster parents keep us separate.  Other dogs are a hard no for me.  I want 100% of the attention from my future family!

I am medium energy, about 60 lbs, crate trained (I like to sleep at night in there), love snuggling on the couch, enjoy belly and butt scratches, drool at the thought of a bone slathered with peanut butter inside, am pretty darn good at fetch, and know how to sit like a good girl.  I am okay with cats and haven’t been tested with kids yet. 

My foster mom says I act like some other animal called a deer because of the way I leap around the backyard.  Oh how I’d love if my future family had a big fenced in backyard for me to run around in— I love to run and leap, but not for too long because I’d much prefer to be laying on my back like a baby in the lap of someone who loves me.

Because I get nervous with new people initially, continual support will be needed post adoption, therefore, upon locating my right family, IBR would like to financially support training classes for me and my new family to ensure I’m set up for a long successful life.  I have already been attending some classes to work on my manners.  

If you think you can give me a no-dog, patient, energetic, loving home please consider putting in an app for me!  I dream of a person of my own one day!

animal.description:
~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST ~ PLZ DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~
If you are interested in this dog,  Please apply in person during adoption hours at the Manchester Animal Shelter in Manchester, NH. Check their hours online: https://www.manchesteranimalshelter.org/

Fiona is a very sweet 6-year old, 46-pound pocket pittie located near Manchester, NH. She’s spayed, house-trained, and up-to-date on vaccines. She has been in a loving foster home during the pandemic which has enabled her to grow into herself after a very long shelter stay. She will need a special adopter to help her continue this journey of discovery.

Fiona really enjoys being with people, going on low-key outings, playing, taking walks, and cuddling. Once she knows people, she will wag her tail and give a snuggle. This is amazing considering her background. Fiona was in poor shape when picked up as a stray in 2019. Malnourished and mangey, you would never know she is the same dog today. This petite gal is a survivor who started her road to recovery once under the care of our friends at the Manchester Animal Shelter. 
It took over a year until she was finally healthy and strong. Finding the right diet and medications, and learning to trust people again. Now she goes on outings where she ventures to public places and continues to amaze us with the progress, she makes each time! She was so stubborn at first when we initially started training, and now she thoroughly enjoys it. She is highly intelligent, and she knows it! 
Fiona loves to be out in the yard. She sunbathes and rolls around on her back, legs flailing in the air, just soaking up her happy place. She will stalk birds and squirrels and enjoys sounding the alarm, so everyone knows there is a person at the door. Fiona also does well in the car. Whatever gets her out of the shelter is good enough for her! She receives an outstanding report every time the foster checks in. She does well in a home, has no accidents, and doesn’t seem too upset being there alone. She just settles into a comfy spot, watches Animal Planet, and waits for the foster dad to return home. She’s loves the simple things in life!  

Introductions with this beauty will need to go slow to ensure a smooth transition. way she was treated by previous humans, could have left her aggressive and lost, but the inner power of a pit bull shines through instead. Fiona needs to be the only fur-kid in an adult-only home. No kids or busy apartment complexes please. It may be possible for her to live with older, mature teenagers, so please email your situation to the address below if that is the case. 

To apply for the prize pittie, contact canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org and tell them ARK sent you!

animal.description:
She is a young two year old, highly athletic, beautiful tri-color bully blend who entered our facility a little over 9 months ago. Zaylee came to us after enduring highly unstable circumstances. Living a transient lifestyle where she was frequently left alone in the woods, tied to various objects when her owners were not around. Understandably, she does not respond well to strangers who approach her kennel and is uneasy around new situations and people she doesn't know. It is important her new family understands this uneasiness, to avoid putting her at risk for a misunderstanding. Zaylee takes her time getting to know you before giving you her immense love and devotion. Given a little patience, respect and kindness she really comes out of her shell and illuminates a heart that is made of pure gold. Zaylee is young with puppy like energy. She loves to be silly, run zoomies, splash in the water, play fetch and search for those pesky gophers. While she loves to run and play she also enjoys chilling out with her favorite humans on the sofa and unwinding with some her favorite toys. Zaylee has responded very well to harness training and is our preferred method of working with her. She knows how to sit and stay and would love to continue working on her training with you. A home with adults or older teens is preferred. This bubbly little lady will flourish with experienced owners who can give her time, patience, love and structure. Zaylee can become reactive to other dogs and small animals. She would really shine and thrive as the only pet in the home. UTD on all shots, vaccines, spayed and in great health. She really struggles with the stress and boredom of kennel life and is ready to be rescued!  Please contact Del Norte Animal Control (707) 464-7235 if you are interested in meeting Zaylee!

 Come check out our other dogs available for adoption at 2650 Washington Blvd, Crescent City, CA 95531.

We pre-screen adopters interested in the Pit Bull Terrier blends at Del Norte Animal Control, and an adoption application will be required from those interested in providing a fab furever home to Zaylee.  Please call us at (707) 464-7235 for additional information.  More photos of this dog may be available on the Dogs of Del Norte County Facebook page.

animal.description:
Millie Mae is a bouncy, happy, active young adult.  She absolutely loves
people, and will soak up pets, belly rubs, and snuggles. She still jumps
for joy when greeting people - as a tall and lanky 75# dog, her
enthusiasm can be a hazard to children and seniors. A large overbite
gives her a giant beaming smile.  When not basking in attention or
sleeping, she trots around exploring or entertains herself playing.
Millie is a country girl, having spent most of her life outdoors in a
fenced yard or chicken run.  She was not potty trained as a puppy, but
has not had any accidents in the small portion of our house we have
allowed her into.  We think she can learn house manners with patience
and training - and know she would be delighted to spend more time with
people.  Her first family had fowl, doves and rabbits.  We believe Millie is safe with poultry and has expressed only curiosity about our neighbor's cows and horses.  She is not a livestock guardian, but her big, deep bark alerts to approaching cars and people.
We have started teaching Millie basic commands, and she is a fast
learner.  She has walked our
property well on a long retractable leash, and has been manageable on a
short leash during trips to town.

Please visit www.txpyrs.org for more information and to fill out an application.

Texas Great Pyrenees Rescue, Inc. is a 501(c)(3) organization dedicated to Great Pyrenees. We have the best selection of Pyrs in Texas and we do home checks and vet checks before placement. We start with adoption applications (no cost/obligation) and we make placements on a first submitted-first approved basis. If you are interested in giving this dog a new home, please complete an adoption form found at http://www.txpyrs.org

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: December 16, 2018 Size: 55 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING EGGY
Eggy wandered up on a woman's porch in Twiggs County, GA, trying to get in her home on a freezing cold night. The elderly woman was terrified of dogs and her rural county does not have an Animal Control. The police would not approach Eggy as they said he was being fearful. Luckily, our friends at nearby Macon-Bibb Animal Control sprang into action to secure the dog and Jason drove 3 hours, late in the evening on December 10th, 2019 to pick him up. Eggy is a special boy and he was lovingly named in honor of our founder, Jason's, late brother who passed away 15 years ago. Eggy was his brother's childhood nickname and his birthday is on December 18th, just a few days away from Eggy's freedom ride.
ABOUT EGGY
It was very apparent from his condition that some extremely bad things have happened to Eggy. He clearly suffered tremendously and we are grateful to be the positive start to his journey. Dear, sweet Eggy is Forlorn no more and will know nothing but love from here on out. Eggy was evaluated by our vet and has a long list of ailments. His condition was so critical, he had to undergo surgery to clean and repair multiple lacerations and have part of his tail amputated as it was down to the bone. Luckily, his bloodwork came back good. There were remnants of a buck-shot and bone fragments on his x-rays consistent with a gunshot wound to the face. He was loaded with intestinal parasites, fleas, and ticks. Along with the wounds all over his body, Eggy had pressure sores down to the bone. He was so thin and malnourished that his body condition score was a 1 out of 9. Poor Eggy suffered far too long from neglect and abuse, but to top it all off, Eggy had an advanced case of heartworms that have since been treated. His healing journey is one for the record books, but despite his condition, Eggy is strong, sweet, and wagging his tail (or shall we call it a nub!). Eggy loves his shenanigans and his favorite game is 'keep-away,' where he will merrily zoom around the yard with his Kong in his mouth, leaving the Palace workers to chase after him when it's time to come inside. He is looking for a forever family where he can keep on enjoying the good life of a beloved house pet. Eggy has been through more than we can imagine and he is not suited for a home with other pets or small children. If you think you can give Eggy the life he so desperately wants and deserves, contact us for more information!
Photo Album of Eggy: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=3115449728513172
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Bishop is one of our dogs who needed a "little extra" in terms of training to get him ready for a wonderful forever home.

He came into the rescue from an animal advocate who had rescued him from a bad situation but was unable to keep him. We saw Bishop posted on a free pets site and reached out to her. After meeting him, we agreed to bring him into the rescue.

We thought we had a foster in place for Bishop. However plans sometime don't materialize. When the foster placement fell through, Bishop spent much longer than was ideal in boarding at our vet's office. He is a young, active, high-energy dog, and time in the boarding kennel took its toll on him.

Thankfully, a good friend of our rescue agreed to take Bishop into her home and has done some foster-based training with him. 

Bishop has excelled in his training! It took him a couple of weeks to relax and decompress and, once that happened, he proved himself to be a happy student.

Bishop is now able to stay on all four feet when excited.  He sits nicely and patiently waiting for his meals. He walks well on a leash. He has learned that there are more appropriate ways to seek attention than using his mouth. He knows his basic commands. In short, Bishop is now ready to move to a wonderful forever home!

We would like to see Bishop in a home with a family experienced with the breed.

He will do best as an only pet, and in an adult home or one with children 16 years old or older.

We'd love to see Bishop in a home with a fenced yard where he can run and play. He also needs a family who will take him out and about, and continue to introduce him to new people, places, and things.

If you would like to adopt Bishop, please fill out the application at our website: https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCEDURES:

Our goal is to help you find a wonderful new family member! We work closely with you to ensure that the dog you adopt will be a wonderful match for your family's make-up and lifestyle. Our adoption and foster placement processes includes an application, personal and vet reference checks, a home visit, and a meet and greet with the dog and all family members and other pets.

Placement is considered on the basis of the best interests of the dog and the best fit with the family - we do not adopt on a "first come, first served" basis.

We do not transport our dogs outside of the state of CT. If you live outside of CT and are able to travel to us after an application is approved, with your family and other pets, for a meet and greet and to complete the adoption in CT if that goes well, you're welcome to apply to adopt one of our dogs, as long as you live in one of the New England states. We do not adopt our dogs long-distance, or outside of the New England area.

PLEASE NOTE:  All of our dogs live in foster homes within the state of CT.  We do not have a facility.  For that reason we ask that you go through the application/approval process prior to a meet and greet, which is always part of our placement protocol.  We do this because we try to keep our foster families' day to day lives s uninterrupted as possible. You can fill out an adoption application at our website, at https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application .

animal.description:
Meet Milo! I am a 5 year-old, handsome, loving, and smart guy in search of an active, outdoorsy family. I prefer adults. Other dogs (with proper introduction) should be big like me. I have the most expressive eyes, accented with manly outlines of black hair, do well on a leash, and know quite a few basic commands, including "sit", "stay", "wait", "release", "down", "stack", and "look at me". Do you think you could learn these commands, too? Also, I would love a home with fenced yard to keep me safe, no cats, and a grain-free diet to keep me healthy.

From Foster Family: 
Things we’ve learned about Milo since we’ve had him:
•	He likes walks on the beach, and playing in the waves.  He also enjoys chasing rivers, but he is ambivalent about lakes and ponds. 
•	He loves walks in the woods - his nose is always working.  This can make for very slow going if it’s a trail where a lot of other dogs have been or very fast going if he happens upon a snake or rabbit to chase (reminder:  he is VERY strong!). 
•	He is always excited for a car ride, but does not always appreciate strangers (like baristas or cashiers) talking to you.  But, yes, he would like a puppucino, thanks for asking. 
•	He is VERY food motivated.  Except lettuce, he doesn’t like that - but it is worth giving it to him to watch him spit it out.  Also keep in mind that he is counter height (He seems to have learned not to get up there anymore, but I still wouldn’t leave out any temptations.)  
•	He gets VERY excited when his people come home.  He likes to greet you at the door with a gift.  He used to pick shoes, but he’s learned to get one of his own toys now. It’s super sweet and cute.
•	He likes to look at the window, deer are his favorite.  Also a good time to remember that he is stronger than the screen if there is a cat, rabbit, or deer outside.
•	He is a big fan of comfort - apparently only peasants chew their bones on the floor.  A dog of his caliber requires a nice couch, bean bag or dog bed.  It may or may not matter to him if you are already sitting there.
•	Don’t believe ANY stuffed animal that tries to make you think it’s a match for him.  It’s not.  
•	He does not appreciate it if you stop rubbing his belly and is not shy in letting you know about it. 
•	Similarly, he does not like to take “no” for an answer.  He usually will, but sometimes if he is very excited or in a surly mood - watch your fingers.
•	Impulse control is not always his jam.  But he really does want to be good.  
•	He’s very protective.  Besides the baristas, he’s also saved us from the UPS guy, and the noisy furnace.  I also feel safe with him on trails.

The best way I can think of to describe Milo is that he’s like having a very large, strong, opinionated four year old.  Meaning, he is super adorable and very fun, but a lot of work.  And worth it.  

If you have further questions or would like to schedule an appointment to meet me in person, please contact the adoption team at Shelton Adopt-a-Pet. Emails are the preferred method of communication.

Telephone: (360) 432-3091

And although she's a senior she has many happy and active years left to go. At 5-6 more to go! She's been good with some dogs both male and female, but not all dogs. She can be a bit bossy and pushy on first encounters. If the other dog is friendly and submissive, she'll follow verbal commands and handler reprimands. Learns quick and obeys well. This dog needs a LARGE fenced yard! 100$ donation. Please contact the rescue at pangaya@msn.com or text 602-689-8506 for more info or to set up a meet and greet.

Please note that at this time we are not able to respond to every application. It is crucial that you read the dog's bio to make sure that she is a match before you apply. If she is a match, we will respond within 48 hrs.  
Maggie is a little female long haired chihuahua/doxie maybe spaniel mix who was dropped off at the shelter because her family did not want the responsibility of taking care of her.   She is 9 yrs old and around 8 lbs she does not take up much room at all.  Maggie is slow to trust however if you take time to get to know her she is sweet, loves being a lap dog and getting belly rubs and asks to be picked up and carried.  She is very loyal and bonds quickly and follows her person around the house all the time.  She loves attention and treats but she is is food/treat possessive and resource guards so a very experience home with no dominant dogs would be best.   Maggie is also fear aggressive at times, when she knows she is in trouble or when you reach for her too quickly she will bite, so her owner has to be careful and familiar with fearful dogs and be ready for continuous training.   We know she can be amazing in the right home as she has come such a long way in terms of trust, but she needs that dedicated adopter to help her stay on track.  No children for this pup.  While she is housetrained she does act out at times with inappropriate urination, so again lots of stability would be best for her.
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption. 
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Re-Listed for adoption: 12/7/2020
Adoption fee: $250
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

animal.description:
Olivia is in love with all people she meets!  She wants to be around humans wherever they go and snuggling with her people is one of her absolute favorite activities.  Olivia's foster family reports she is really a sweetheart and always enjoys her people's full one on one attention. While Olivia loves attention, she will still require a home with a family who can provide firm, consistent rules, boundaries, leadership and a very consistent routine for her.  She is a “resource guarder” of all types (food, water, human interaction, toys) and she is definitely has the “bully” personality.  Her adoptive family must always remind her of her place in the home and that she comes "2nd".  Again, she must have a very firm, consistent owner who will set a firm routine with clear rules and boundaries for her in her adoptive home.  She would also do best if there were no other dogs in the household in her adoptive home.  She is insecure around other dogs and this manifests into dog aggression, especially when energy levels are higher (during play times or any excitement in the home), so a home with no other dogs will absolutely be required for her. Her foster family continues to work with her to correct unwanted behaviors as needed as, again, she does tend to resource guard things like human attention and toys and does not hesitate to try and start a fight with another dog over something she wants or considers hers. She has met children as young as 1 year old and has done well with them, but she does not really have the energy for young, rambunctious/active children.  Due to this, a home with older, easy going, respectful, dog savvy children 12 years or older will be preferred for her.  Again, she wouldn’t mind older children being around/visiting from time to time, but they’d need to be dog savvy and respectful and be able to understand her needs - treating her VERY gently and not treating her as a roughhouse playmate. As with all dogs, Olivia should always be supervised around children to ensure that both she and they are kept safe.  Olivia seems to be a typical loafer Frenchie, but does still like to play for short brisk periods of time. She has very short bursts of energy to bark at a dog on other side of fence or play with a toy in the house for a few times.  

Olivia has been working on potty training with her foster family but still needs time to improve her skills in this area. Due to her medication's side effects (increased thirst and urination) it complicates her potty training and inability to hold her bladder. It does help to have her on a very consistent potty break schedule and having frequent potty breaks helps her eliminate accidents - at *least* every 3-4 hours is best for helping avoid accidents. She may never be considered fully “potty trained” because she simply can’t always help it (especially so if her adoptive family is not very consistent in her potty routine) due to her medication's side effects. Olivia needs to have limited access to drinking water (hand offer only multiple times a day) due to limiting accidents and she has an obsession to drink and will forget to potty first.   Olivia has done well with crate training when her foster family happens to leave the home and seems comfortable there with a fluffy blanket/bed to sleep on and nylabone or two to keep her busy during the night or daytime when her family is away from the home.  If her family works away from the home during the daytime, again, she will need to be let out every 3-4 hours to avoid having accidents in her crate.  Again, she does not do as well "holding it" due to the medications she takes for her medical condition. For her safety, we recommend that she keep a similar crating schedule when her humans are away from the home and/or she is left unsupervised so that she is safe and secure while no one is home.


Medically, Olivia has a condition called Immune Mediated Polyarthritis (IMPA). Due to this her activity needs to be somewhat limited so as not to put excess stress on her joints. Her potential adopters will need to understand that her medical condition requires them to be diligent in treating her IMPA:  she is on a lifelong Immunosuppressant drugs (approximate cost is $26 a month for her meds). Her current daily regimen is Leflunomide and Prednisone and she requires bloodwork every 6 months for maintenance due to her medications. She is also on a daily joint supplement (Dogzymes Phytoflex) and should also remain on that for the remainder of her lifetime.  Her current joint flareups are mostly controlled  with her medications but she still has good days and bad days. With having an immune disorder, this also predisposes her to other potential illnesses, especially as she ages. Olivia Rose is spayed, microchipped is up to date on vaccinations/deworming and heartworm preventative and has no other known health issues. 

Olivia’s ideal home will be a fenced in yard with no pool and/or near any size body of water, and no full flights of stairs (minimal stairs inside and outside are ok) to keep her from having joint flare ups. If her people did not have a fenced yard, that's okay too, very short leashed harnessed walks (no collars) would be just fine. Her people will also need to prevent her from jumping on and off of furniture as much as possible in order to help prevent joint flare ups/damage that would result from her jumping a lot. Above all, she would prefer a family that likes to spend a LOT of time at home and will shower her with lots attention and cuddles. She does not travel well (due to the stress of her joints), and boarding at a facility is not an option for her due to stress, so she would likely require a dog sitter if her adoptive family were traveling out of town without her.  Due to her need for so many potty breaks (every 3-4 hours minimum), she would also be really happy to live with a stay at home dog parent or someone who works from home. She could be a great pup to take to work so long as she was the only pup there (or can be kept separate from other dogs) and if it was a quiet and easy going work environment. If her people are not able to take her to work with them, no problem - she's completely happy sleeping the day away in her kennel with a nylabone to chew on as long as her people can arrange the necessary multiple (every 3-4 hours minimum) mid day potty breaks for her!   

 
If you feel like your family might be the perfect forever home for Olivia, please submit an adoption application for her today!!

If you're looking for a new best friend, couch buddy, hiking partner, please look no further than sweet 4 year old Titan! The only joke being placed is on the people who don't adopt this boy!

Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Buttons is a two year old American Bulldog mix who came to us to find her forever place!  This girl is so happy and a bundle of energy - she needs an active family and a fenced in yard to make sure she can get the time to run around to burn off some of her energy.    

Buttons weighs around 60 pounds and would be recommended for kids age 9 and up.  Her size and energy can knock little ones over - she loves kids, but she gets so excited!   Buttons pulls hard on a leash, so she needs someone willing to use a gentle leader or work on other training to help with this.    When Buttons is out for a walk, she gets super excited when she sees kids or other dogs, and she just wants to pull to get to them so she can say hello.  

Buttons was surrendered to a shelter because she had too much energy, and she didn't have another dog to play with so she was looking to her humans for everything she needed.  She would chase after the cat in the home.  She would love a playful friend to run around with!   Buttons does good in a crate, but will make a little noise at times when her humans are leaving to go to work for the day.  She will need a little housetraining refresher whenever she moves to a new home because the house set up and the routine is different than what she's used to.   

After Buttons came to rescue, we found out that both of her ACL's on her back legs were torn, and would require surgery.  Buttons has had both leg surgeries during 2020 and she is doing fantastic! 

Buttons loves other dogs and she loves to play!  She is an amazing friendly and happy girl!  

Adoption fee is $350.00 (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie @ kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

I am a 3-year-old Shar-Pei mix weighing 55#. Don’t let my looks fool you, I am a big baby! 

I am friendly with people when I am not on my turf (house/yard). I will need time (anf lots of treats) to warm up to a stranger. 

I walk well on a leash, but will react toward animals on a leash. I am animal aggressive in general and need to be an ONLY PET in the home. I have not been desensitized to small children. They kind of freak me out for some reason. Teens are cool :)

What can I say I am a  is a typical, poorly socialized Pei. My dominant and territorial nature is normal, but difficult to manage. I will require consistent follow through with my training including socialization with other dogs (on a leash on walks) and territorial behavior. 

Free in-home training comes with my adoption fee.

Can only be adopted out locally to get training assistance (NKY/Cincinnati)

I LOVE to go on walks and although my size maybe intimidating don't worry I'm actually really good on a leash. we have recently came to the realization that Ace may possibly be deaf or hearing impaired. if you have experience with a deaf dog and may be looking to open your home to a lovable giant please consider Ace.To adopt me, please visit valleyanimal.org/adoption-info/ to download the Pre-Adoption Application and email dogs@valleyanimal.org to make an appointment to meet me! 

"also If you are looking for a young dog to take on hiking trips or to the beach, there is nothing I enjoy more than exploring new places so I am definitely the perfect adventure buddy!" -Ace

animal.description:
(Version française disponible ici:  

https://www.sitwithme.ca/fr/dogs/gilbert/)

Gilbert

Shepherd Mix

11 years old

Male



Dogs: Absolutely no. 

Cats: No, thanks

Kids: 8+

Housing Type: Detached or townhome. He is mostly quiet but needs a dog-free environment.

Fenced-in yard: Preferred, but not necessary

Special needs: Gilbert requires a gastro diet.



This handsome dude is searching for his kindred spirit!  He loves every human he meets and every human cannot get over what a lovely boy he is too!



Gilbert came into rescue with severe wounds after being attacked by several other dogs. He has completely healed externally, but he did lose one of his eyelids.


As you can imagine, Gilbert is searching for a home where there are no other pets after his ordeal. He is not good with other dogs and wants very badly to chase cats when he sees them. He doesn’t require a fenced in yard if his people are comfortable walking him knowing he will have a reaction when he sees other dogs out and about. Gilbert would much prefer a fenced in yard where he can follow his nose safely and without the worry of running into other dogs.  He would love play time with his person in the fenced in yard in lieu of walks.



His kindred spirit is someone who is home more often than not (although he can be left alone just fine) and understands that Gilbert just wants to love and be loved by his people. Gilbert hasn’t lived with children, but he’s very well behaved with the children that he’s met. Because of his size, we think he’d do better with older children. 



He is a lover, a best friend, and all the makings of a true soulmate for the right home.  While he has other pet restrictions which may make him harder to place, we also know what he gives back in return is pretty special.  He is worth it.



Gilbert is hoping his forever people love reading - he’s a literary fellow after all! In the words of LM Montgomery, “when you are imagining, you might as well imagine something worthwhile.” We imagine that by now you are almost as in love with Gil as we are and are picturing your life together. 

If you think you are a match for Gil, complete our online application: http://www.sitwithme.ca/dogs/gilbert

animal.description:
This sweet boy is one of our Hurricane Dorian rescues.  He was pulled out of an overflowing shelter in Georgia by the CORES group (Coalition of Ontario Rescues for Emergency Support), so that dogs displaced from the Bahamas could move in and receive assistance. 

Sailor is a happy-go-lucky little guy who’s had a hard start to this life.  He doesn’t have good use of his hind end but it doesn’t seem to slow him down.  Sailor loves being around loving humans and enjoys playing with other dogs his own speed, or will happily play on his own.  He can play with other dogs with toys or tug-of-war with a human, or he can participate in ‘chase-me’ with gentle dogs; he may need to be gently corrected at times when he gets too excited while playing, but overall he’s quite laid back.  One of his favourite things to do is snuggle up with his favourite human or pup to feel secure and loved.  Sailor loves to be outside in nice weather and is the perfect buddy on a warm afternoon.  He is unknown about his interactions with cats or young children.  Sailor does not like loud or sudden noises and will bark at something that startles him.  He sleeps well through the night on his own dog bed.  His foster family describes him as ‘one of the biggest sweethearts’ they’ve ever fostered.  Sailor loves attention, cuddling, playing, and is just a happy pup.

Requirements:
-fully secured fenced yard (no electric fence)
-no apartments
-if another dog in the home, must be calm and respectful dog that is less than 40 lbs
-respectful children in the home must be at least 7 years old

Medical Note:  Sailor has had Vertebral malformation at T12 with kyphosis at T12-T13. Which is a compression of his spine due to some kind of trama.  We have consulted with a couple of veterinarians on what we could do for him and unfortunately there is not much that could be done if we are to take into account his well-being and quality of life.  Whoever adopts him will need understand that he does have a disability and be financially stable to take this on in the future if something were to happen down the road, they will also need to understand he cannot be climbing stairs or jumping off furniture as this can cause more damage to his spine.  We are hopeful to see Sailor in a fitted wheelchair soon to help run as fast as he wants to.

Because of these injuries, Sailor’s bathroom manners will need to be worked with.  At this time, he may still have accidents in the home and can have a difficult time when going in the yard, but his foster family says that he does a pretty good job of keeping himself clean.  It is our hope to see Sailor in a fitted wheelchair to assist with mobility and bathroom issues, which will require a family willing to work with him through his stages of learning.

SCAR does not have the resources to adopt animals to the United States and we can only adopt within a 200 km radius of Windsor, Ontario.  Please do not apply if you do not live in Ontario, within 200 kms of Windsor.
https://secondchanceanimalrescuewe.wordpress.com/adoptdog/

animal.description:
PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/ellafitzgerald

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies under 1 year of age.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.
