animal.description:
Chance came back to us when major family issues made it impossible for Chance to stay with his family.

Chance's family consisted of two adults and two young children. Chance did wonderfully with the children and now plays with other dogs in his foster home.

Chance is spayed and has all necessary vaccinations. She would love to be part of an active household that include her in family activities. She is still a youngster and is full of energy, things to consider when thinking about adoption.
Chance's foster family says she is a fabulous sweet girl.


Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Chance or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.
animal.name: Chance

animal.special_needs_notes: He was abused. He does not like to be picked up under his front legs, does not like to be grabbed by the back of his collar. He needs an experienced loving patient person with experience with an abused dog. He is super affectionate and once he trusts you he will roll and play and kiss you and follow you anywhere. He is super smart and will jump on lap on command and will get down on command. He was abused so if you try to do those things he is scared of, he will bite, not nip. Once he knows you as he does me after four months, he will trust you but you still have to be careful. If you have experience with a dog that has been abused and will bite if touched the wrong way and you have the patience to gain his trust, you are the right owner for him.

animal.description:
My name is Matilda, I love to chase birds in the yard, play fetch and be with my parents. I think I am a guard dog, I love to bark at everything outside of my yard! It is my job to keep my yard safe! I also bark at the suspicious sounds at night. I go to the door and stand when I need to go potty. Sometimes I'm stubborn if I think I can get my way. I have had basic training so I know what no, sit, stay and down means. I need some refreshing sometimes. If there are treats involved I'm always a good listener. I don't share my food or bones though. I like other dogs that respect my personal space and give me some time to make sure they will be nice to me. I don't mind cats if they don't mind me.

She's a unique dog that needs a unique owner, can that be you?
&


We are not a shelter, we are a rescue and all of our rescued pets live with a Tennessee foster family until their forever home is found. They are all checked by a veterinarian, current on their vaccinations, spayed/neutered are micro-chipped. Our fosters know the animals best and will give you an honest assessment of their traits and training. 


If you are interested in adopting a pet from Saving The Animals Together, please submit an application by clicking on the Adopt tab at www.savingtheanimalstogether.org or email us at statadoptions@savingtheanimalstogether.org 


As soon as we receive your application back, we will check your references and then contact you for a telephone interview. At that point the foster will contact you to discuss the pet with you.

animal.description:
Gracie is in temp foster care and we would like another foster for her as soon as possible. Please contact us if you wish to foster or foster with intent to adopt. If you are interested in adopting Gracie please go to our website www.jcldr.com and fill out an adopt application. No one is obligated by doing so but it is a good starting place.  Long-distance transport can be discussed.

UPDATE FROM TEMP FOSTER 1/2020: Such a sweet, respectful, mellow girl in the house. Love her. Outside very curious,  up for chasing critters for sure, completely different girl. Well rounded. Absolutely no other dogs for now. Respectful through 3-foot gate with other dogs. Just doesn't like her space invaded, quick to react negatively. I always say I would keep her for myself if she was the one and only. 

Meet Gracie: She is a spayed female Catahoula, 2 & ½ years old, she could be a purebred but appears to be a mix. Weight 68 pounds, up to date on Vaccs, HW tested Negative and is started on Heartguard. Microchipped.  Handles well at the vets but uneasy till she gets acquainted.  (Admin Note: Not unusual with Catahoulas. No major restraints needed.) Crate broken, housebroken, fed twice a day. She seems to be very good about excessive vocal restraint. She is not good with small children, she seems to like 8 to 10-year-old children that are dog respectful.  She is a good companion type dog and not excessively reactive on leash though uneasy when other dogs come around. She would be best an only dog. Gracie was surrendered to a veterinary clinic and we will give detail about that by phone. She has been great at the clinic so far with everyone. There are no men at the clinic so we are not sure if a gender unease is there. She is great with the ones handling her and there are a lot of them. She is not cage reactive, interested as dogs walk by but not tens. Clinic staff has worked with her with treats and she follows basic commands and treat and food respectful with a soft mouth. Such a good dog that has been in the three wrong homes and small children left unsupervised were part of the issue and why she was rehomed twice more. She did not act out with the children. 

HISTORY: We don’t know her original history. We know she was thrown in with six dogs and that is a lot stimulus and that is all we know from the first known home. Second home had a small child and probably the dog and baby came to that home about the same time. This home also had a small Pitbull mixed female and they ended up not getting along. She was passed on to a third home after the dog altercation which started mild and escalated. The third home had an 8-month-old baby (ADMIN NOTE: Not a good idea to give a dog that is uneasy with toddlers to another home with toddlers) The new owner moved in with her Mom who had a senior Schnauzer and Gracie had no idea why all this shuffling. She was unsettled, sorting things out and worried no doubt. At first she got on with the little dog, but a day or two things went south. She was taken to clinic to be boarded and found a new home. There was chaos in the first home we know of as the woman had intact dogs and was breeding them. Gracie did show some unease with all of the high stimuli and it was a lot. 

GOOD: While at the clinic these are the things that have been observed about Gracie and all agree she is a great dog. We aren’t sure how she will be in the home but she no doubt would be more relaxed in a good home that is a fit for her. She keeps her kennel clean, happy to see everyone and greets all across the board the same. She not very vocal, She has not been on leash much at the clinic so there is no way to know if she is a leash puller or leash reactive. Very food motivated, performing her basic commands. Not reactive in her kennel or cage, only shows excited interest in the cat and we think more negative. No kitties for her. Everyone loves Gracie. Dogs going past her kennel and even excessive barking dogs, she will react a bit with them by barking but only excessive barkers that are next door kennel mates broke her composure. Second owner says that she is a great dog in the house, is totally housebroken, no issues in the car with them traveling, calm and sweet. She is not a kisser but she is a leaner, and wants to be close to you. 

BAD: She likes her clean cage so she pushes newspapers out. That is the only bad that has shown up. She roughs it up and pushes it out but she holds her urination and stools for a long long time.  She doesn't like other dogs. 


UGLY: In the last home where the Schnauzer and Gracie decided they did not like each other, we do not know who started the dog fight. We will try to find out from the previous owner. The older lady in the home, owner of the small dog, reached in on the dog fight and got bitten. A few minor punctures, so Gracie has been in quarantine for the required period of time. Her jail time is up now.  When she was in her second home there was a dog fight in that home between the Pitty girl and her. This was the first big fight but they had other small altercations between them at night while the people were asleep. (ADMIN NOTE: After the first middle of the night fight, one of the dogs should have been crated. Both females and no supervision and no way to know who or what started it)   They had her for almost two years before the fighting started. She was great with the young child who was allowed to crawl all over her but that isn't a wise thing to allow to happen.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Moe. I am a five-year-old chocolate Lab. I have a very soft coat with light brown highlights. I was even mistaken for a puppy because my coat looks so shiny. We go for walks and swim which is my favorite thing to do. I am a super sweet boy but I have some separation and confinement anxiety so I need a family who will have patience with my adjustment period. I am on medication for my anxiety and will need to continue it until I am fully comfortable in my new home. I have been working with a trainer who says I’m a super quick learner. I know sit and paw and I ALMOST do  ‘down'. I get excited when I meet someone new but my fosters have been working with me to sit when I see someone new instead of jumping. I LOVE my kong toy especially when you put peanut butter inside and retrieving toys you throw in the water. I love to cuddle and sit politely by you when I want attention which is always.
I’m looking for a special home where I’d be the only pet. I need someone who will work with me on my training. If you think we’d make a good fit, come visit me in Plantation!



If you are interested in adopting please go to LRRoF.org NOW and fill out an application.

Thanks so much for your interest in our rescue!
Your support, both through adoption and donation is always essential to us and our Labs. Donate today!
We're about matching the right dog with the right family. All applicants will be assigned an Adoption Counselor who will act as their liaison. In addition, a phone interview, home inspection and vet reference (if applicable) are required for eligibility to adopt from Labrador Retriever Rescue of Florida.

Ollie has come a long way since he came to the Sanctuary. He used to be really shy with strangers, but now he pulls his caregivers towards new volunteers to meet them. Ollie has a generous sponsor who will cover his adoption costs.

animal.description:
Last weigh-in: 42.2 lbs

Hello new friends, I'm Arya! 
Not too long ago, I was pregnant and looking for a place to deliver and nurse my litter of puppies. I found an old building in Uptown, and decided to nest in the crawl space for shelter. It was in that crawl space that I delivered my three puppies and nursed them for 3-4 weeks. During that time, a nice man and woman brought me food and water. I was scared of them, and always ran away when they came near, but I was thankful for the nourishment they left for me. They also checked on my puppies, but left them alone so that I could keep taking care of them. 
Over Labor Day weekend, the woman came to visit me and I ran out from under the house. Outside, I found a trail of tasty chicken leading to a metal frame of some kind. I followed the trail, which resulted in her being able to humanely and safely "trap me". After I was secure, she transported my puppies and I to her home. Once there, she set us up with a cozy area to rest and nurse. It turns out that the woman discovered that the house we were nestled under was scheduled to be demolished after Labor Day so I am really glad that she saved us!
I have been in the care of the nice woman ever since. She has helped me raise my puppies, as well as found them loving forever homes where they will never be in harm's way. With the puppies taken care of, now she wants to help me find forever home!
The vet estimates that I am about 1.5-2 years old and a Shepherd mix. I like other dogs, but I have not had the chance to meet any kids or kitties yet. I am going to be starting heartworm treatment soon, now that my puppies are all weaned. I am still pretty unsure of a leash, harness, collar, walking scenario. However,, after I get healthy, I promised my foster mom that I will really start working on trying new things and being more open to the idea of love. I am very excited about my future as a Streedog!

animal.description:
True is a loving, intelligent, loyal companion.  She gives hugs and kisses and enjoys her morning cuddles and belly rubs.  She’s eager to please and learn.  She is currently seeking an adoptive home or a foster home while she awaits her forever home.
  True is considered a medium energy dog, meaning that she likes to run and play ball for about 10-15 times in a row 2-3 times a day and she’s a happy girl.  Or you can take her for a walk.  As long as she gets some form of brief exercise 2-3 times a day, she’s pretty content.  
  True does well with dogs that are not crazy energy and that will back off when she is done playing.  True is NOT good with cats.  She has an intense prey drive and loves to chase whatever comes into the yard. Squirrels, birds, bunnies, bees, you name it she will chase it.
  True does have some issues with resource guarding that we are currently working on.  This is the main reason we have decided to say “no kids” to True’s new family. Resource guarding is not that abnormal for a dog that had been on their own for a long time like we believe her to have been, Although it’s not a behavior that should be allowed in a home, when caught early, it’s easily trained out of a dog, but in True’s case, it may be something she struggles with for a long time.  Having said this, it’s important for us to note that she has made vast improvements and has learned “leave it” and “drop it” commands.  We have learned many of True’s triggers and simply remove them from the environment.  True responds to verbal commands 
  True is on a daily pill for hypothyroidism that manages many of the symptoms she was having when she came to us such as fur loss, dry skin, and soreness.  The medication requires a simple blood test (T4) every few months (depending on how stable her numbers are).  True is doing GREAT on her medication.  She has regrown all of her fur and it can be classified as luscious now.  Her skin is perfect and there is no signs of body soreness at all.  
  Have additional questions about True?  Feel free to email us.  If interested in fostering or adopting True, fill out the appropriate application at the link below
https://forms.gle/gw9k5r2ArJwJyVm87

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Oscar, one of the most charismatic, lovable seniors here on The Rescue Train. I came aboard from the South Los Angeles Animal Shelter during The Rescue Train's annual Race For The Rescues fundraiser. I am so relieved to be safe and in a nice cozy foster home as the shelter is no place for a sweet ol' fella like me.

My foster parents say that while I'm pretty chill, but I would do best in an ADULT only home with no children. I am very dog/cat friendly and enjoy being around my people...maybe a little too much! Therefore, my foster parents are helping me build my confidence and be more independent. I am crate trained and working on my house breaking. I'd do best in a home with a dog similar in size and energy level.

Some of my favorite activities are curling up on the couch, cuddling and taking long naps. I LOVE getting attention and praise. The words "good boy!" is music to my big cute doggy ears! I have no problem accompanying my humans on long walks...just as long as we're not sprinting in a marathon!

If you think I'm the right fit for you (and most likely, I am!) please consider filling out an application.  XOXO, Oscar

--
If you are interested in adopting OSCAR please go to www.TheRescueTrain.org and fill out our online adoption application on the Adopt A Dog page. Applications are required PRIOR to meeting one of our animals and are used to set up a safe and successful adoption.

Please don't be shy and answer the questions thoroughly. To learn more about our entire process please visit www.therescuetrain.org and click on the Adopt A Dog page or email us at info@therescuetrain.org.

*APPLICANT MUST BE AT LEAST 21 YEARS OLD*
*APPLICANT MUST LIVE IN THE CITY OF LOS ANGELES*

PLEASE NOTE: WE DO NOT OWN A FACILITY. Our animals are in private foster homes. If you are interested in adopting one of our animals please fill out our online application. Or check our mobile adoption schedule on our home page.

animal.description:
Kiwi and her sister Peaches are super playful and smart pups. They are more on the gentle side, not too rambunctious. They even play gently with smaller creatures like cats and rabbits. They are both potty trained and have caught on quickly to simple commands like Sit and Stay. Peaches is the more outgoing of the two. Kiwi is shy at first but quickly warms up. And, both absolutely love each other so cannot be separated. They were born 6/29/2019

We got both of them from the shelter as itty bitty pups, and soon found out that both of them had CHV (Canine Herpesvirus). Most puppies die at 2 weeks from this, however these two were fighters and besides runny noses here and there, are doing really well.  They can have it the rest of their lifes and will be sick from time to time and because there is just not a lot documented on situations like this we have no idea what their future health could be.  They should never be around puppies or attend public places or events, which is another reason we prefer them to be adopted together. 

Included with adoption: Age-appropriate vaccinations, up to date heart-worm preventative, heart-worm test if over 6 months, insurance for 30 days, microchip with registration, and spayed or neutered- if not already, a voucher is provided. 

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our Pre-application: https://form.jotform.us/asr628/ShortAdoptionInquiry

animal.description:
This guy is an absolute staff favorite! 

This is Sir Arthur, a 1 - 2 yr old total lovebug with any human he comes into contact with. He is heartworm negative, neutered, and ready to find his family.

Arthur is a very special guy and needs a special adopter. He does have separation anxiety especially for as long as he has been at the shelter.
He would do really well with someone who spends a lot of time at home or works from home. 
Arthur needs someone that  can help him to feel safe and loved, take him on walks, and let him play in a backyard. 
He is going to make the best and truest companion. 
He LLOOOVVVEEESS people and is the biggest snuggle bug for a tough guy. He also likes to be held like a baby. 

Arthur would need to be an only dog but Arthur will be the only dog you will ever need.
  

ARE YOU THE ONE ARTHUR HAS BEEN WAITING SOOO LONG TO MEET?

Please contact The Horn Lake Animal Shelter for more information and to set up an appointment today.

I am a female Shepherd mix.  I am about 7 years old and weigh approximately 50 lbs.  I am spayed, heartworm negative, current on shots, micro-chipped and on flea/heartworm prevention.  My adoption is $200.

I was originally adopted when I was just a small puppy.  I have gone through training and am, in general, a very well behaved dog and great companion.  I was returned to the rescue because my owner moved into a home without a yard and now that I have to be leash walked, it has become difficult because I can be a bit territorial with other animals.

For the most part, I can be near other pets, however, I can have the propensity to become overbearing and forceful with them so it would be best for me to go to a home without other pets.  While I am not outwardly aggressive in nature, I would also do best without kids.

If I could get a dog savvy owner who is looking for a pal, I would do great.

Please email for an adoption application.
We do not adopt out of state.
Due to many bounced checks, we now require that adoption donations be cash only.  However, if you make a general donation to the organization (not associated with the adoption of a pet) we do accept checks and paypal.  If you are unable to adopt right now, won't you please make a donation to help care for the pets?  THANK YOU!!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 7/13/18

Reason for being in rescue: Found as stray along with a chihuahua one minute from the rescue by a CPR employee. We suspect they were left for us to find.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Lois has a whole lot of special going on. When found, Lois had heartworms. No sooner did we clear those out of her body than she tore both of her back leg cruciate ligaments. This is the ligament that makes the knee work. Oh and she's got a cherry eye that was repaired but it pops back out on its own. Lois has has an epulis which is benign proliferative gum tissue often seen in Boxers.
It can be removed but may recur over a longer period of time.

Weight: Estimated 65 lbs and that is way too much. She needs to be about 50 lbs. She gained a lot of weight during her knee surgeries.
Height: 24" at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1 Lois is priceless

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Lois is a sweetheart of a girl who got handed the short straw when it comes to medical challenges. Her new owner should understand that and know she will be high maintenance, She could be an only dog or share her home with another laid back big dog. She has not spent much time with little dogs since her buddy the chihuahua was adopted. Her new owner will understand that long walks around the block are not in the cards for Lois. She may enjoy swimming as that would be easy on her knees but we've not had her in a pool.

What is my personality like? Lois is a young boxer mix who was found as a stray near our rescue in SC. However, we found her owner about a month after Lois was found and the owner, when she found out Lois had heartworms, never came for her.

Lois is an incredibly sweet girl, with a gentle soul. She gets along well with other dogs and is in a family grouping with Maude the Great Pyrenees and Rafiki the Standard Poodle. She loves to lay on her couch and relax. She loves laying in the sun on the front porch and watching the world go by, She knows how to sit on command and is motivated by treats to learn more tricks. Lois loves squeaky toys and has been known to steal them and collect them at her place in her space. We don't know how long she was out on the streets and she as shy at first but fast forward 18 months and all the handling fixing her many medical issues and that has changed. To those of us who know and love her, she is beautiful and fabulous.

How do I act when I first meet new people? It depends on the person and the place. Lois can be protective of her space. For those she knows and trusts, she is loving and affectionate (and forever hopeful your carrying treats). For those she does not know, you need to be introduced properly or you will not pass her threshold. This may also be pain related as her legs are still not really right. She is overweight and she needs to lose weight to get the pressure off of the, and that's a slow process with bad bum knees.

Other tips and tidbits: Lois was found with the Chihuahua mix, Rio. Rio has been adopted. Lois is truly a rescue. She needs someone who would love a challenge, wants to give a sweet dog a chance, and understands that life is precious. Especially a life affectionately known as Lois

House trained? Lois goes outside to do her business here at the farm on our schedule and routine. Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
BUSTER:  A beautiful 3 1/2 year old  Husky Shepherd mix.  The mom was a purebred Husky and the dad was a husky Shepherd so Buster has some Shepherd but is mostly Husky (he was born in Jan 2017)   

He is a very sweet and happy spirit, playful and friendly!  

He is crate trainedand was house-broken but has been a backyard dog the past couple of years so he will need time to adjust to being in a real home again.....

He comes from a large family of Husky's,that are now in San Jose.  There were 5 siblings, 2 of his sisters have already been adopted....and the owner is going to keep the parents and 2 of the other siblings as they are less adoptable.  

BUSTER is adoptable, but he needs some basic obedience training, don't they all??  

He's good with kids but probably older kids (at least 10 years) so that they can hold their own because he is jumpy...... 

He has only lived with his family since he was a puppy so we aren't completely sure how he would behave around other dogs......!  He might be dominant  so this needs a little more evaluating!

We always recommend a meet and greet so that people can judge for themselves if the dog is in their comfort zone or not!  If not, that's absolutely fine, there's no obligation to adopt!  So please feel free to come out and meet him sometime!

animal.description:
Meet Miss Rayna, our almost 5-year old Rottie/German Shepherd Mix!  She came to us 3 1/2  years ago from an owner surrender and is so scared of everything (men especially, loud noises, cars, delivery trucks, sudden movements, etc)!  Who knows what she's gone through to get her to this stage; we basically have determined her unadoptable because of all her fears.   After this many years, she has accepted her foster family as part of her pack, even though she still barks at her foster dad when he comes into the room from a dark room.  Poor baby!  She has too high a prey drive so NO cats!  She dotes on her foster mom though and will allow her to do just about anything, including cuddle in the chair like the picture!

That doesn't mean that we don't provide her with food, vetting, and any other needs.   She recently was seen by PAN's vet because  she's been limping on her rear right leg for some time and it's not getting any better.   She will probably be on meds for her pain/arthritis long-term which also requires bloodwork to make sure that her kidneys are functioning properly.  

Rayna is spayed and micro-chipped and is kept current on her vaccinations.  Our main page has her as our featured pet and feel free to donate or sponsor Rayna in our quest to make her life more pain-free.

animal.description:
If you can see this dog, she is AVAILABLE. We hide them from view once adopted.

Say hello to Jingle Bells. This beautiful girl is a lab mix whose estimated DOB is 12/2012. Jingle Bells is such a loving girl! She will be a loyal and loving girl to a very lucky person. Jingle Bells doesn't need much to make her happy. Just an occasional walk, a comfy bed to lay on, a full food bowl, and a loving human by her side. This sweetheart has so much love to give and can't wait to find her human who will never leave her!

Jingle Bells is currently in a foster home and has decided she would like to be an only dog. She is extremely devoted to her person, but doesn't love to share with other dog friends. She does ok during an encounter on a walk, so she is not reactive, but she would just prefer her dog friends stay in their own lane. Jingle Bells is quite afraid of men, so a slow intro to men is a must, she is very uneasy about men who come to visit that she does not know. A calm home without a ton of activity is best for this lady.

This dog is heartworm positive. We have started them on the "slow-kill" method of heartworm treatment, but we advise adopters to work with their vets to determine a plan of action. Their adopter will continue treatment once adopted, and arrange a treatment plan with their vet. Dogs with heartworms lead long, happy lives post-treatment!

There is no set adoption fee for this dog. In lieu of an adoption fee we are asking for a donation to our shelter to help us care for these babies and keep them safe. We do not receive any funding so any donation is greatly appreciated

We can offer transport for in-state adopters that cannot make the trip to the shelter.  There is a flat transport fee of $50 to have this dog brought to you.  (This does not apply to meet-and-greets, which must be done at the shelter by appointment only).


ADOPTION FEE AND HEALTH INFORMATION

Upon adoption, she will have received:  age appropriate vaccines (2 DHPP vaccine), (Bordetella vaccine), (Rabies vaccine if 12 weeks and older), up to date on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, spay or neuter of pet, bi-weekly worming, microchip, fostering costs, and health certificate.


APPLY

Isn't she sweet? Wondering what's next?

You MUST fill out an application to adopt. Please copy and paste the Google form URL Below:

https://goo.gl/forms/YKPbHaym6keQA6772


Once you have submitted an application, we do our best to work efficiently to process them. That being said, we are all volunteers that handle adoptions on top of full time jobs, so at times processing can take up to two weeks. 



FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

Q: Where is she located?
A: She is currently at our shelter in Arkansas. She must be adopted locally due to her heart worm status.


Q: I would like to set up a meet and greet!
A: Please fill out an application!  Once approved, we can set up a time where you can go meet her at the shelter.


Q: I have more questions!! Who do I contact?
A: Please e-mail adopt@humanesocietyofthedelta.org directly. We DO NOT answer adoption questions or inquiries on any other platform.


Q: I am under 21, will you adopt to me?
A: Unfortunately, we do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.


Q: I would like to surprise my family with a dog! Can I do this?
A: Unfortunately, no. If there is more than one decision-maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement. 


Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.MUST BE ADOPTED WITH HIS BONDED SISTER, GRACIE! NO SMALL CHILDREN - 10 YEARS OLD AND OLDERGryffin is my name! Yes, I am just this happy and silly. I am a shy little munchkin that needs my sister Gracie. I love to cuddle and spend time each night snuggling down on my foster mom's lap with Gracie. I am a sweet boy. I love to play in the yard with the other fur kids. Mom has lots of trees and plants and we play tag all day long. I love to lay on our pillow in the sun. Mom works in the yard a lot so we are always watched when we are outside. We have a doggie door, so along with the big dogs can come and go as we need to.
In the house, we have a cat tunnel that we play with. It is so funny to run through and make all that crackling noise. I wait until one of my siblings is in the tunnel and then I pounce on them. They squeal - then we run and find a ball or a rope to play tug with.
He was found with his Litter mates in a box next to a dumpster. Who would do that to us? We were saved, and given all the love and care a little girl could ever need. And now, I am getting ready to find my forever home!
I am going to be a very small dog, so mom says NO Small Children in my future. Tiny bones break too easily.
I AM EXTREMELY BONDED WITH MY SISTER, GRACIE, SO WE NEED A FOREVER HOME TOGETHER! If you are interested in meeting me, please apply! I am only doing private meetings. =========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Klint is a 4-5 year old boxer/bully mix. He is around 60lbs and incredibly handsome. He is extremely loving and bonds strongly to his people. He loves to give kisses in return for lots of pets and belly rubs. Unfortunately, Klint has been bounced in and out of a few homes as they didn't have time for him, leaving him alone for 12-13 hours per day. Due to this, he is a dog that does not want to be left alone for long periods of time and prefers a home that will give him the time and attention her deserves.

Klint is in a foster home where he has been learning how to be a great pet. Klint loves being outdoors and thrives in an environment where he can explore outside without interacting with other dogs or strangers. He requires a fenced-in backyard, where he can spend time lying in the sun, and rolling in the shady grass to cool off. He's playful and enjoys chew toys and fetch, especially if there's treats involved! He's well mannered in the home and loves attention, and lots of belly scratches, from his favorite people.  

Klint enjoys the company of ladies, long walks and kids that are 10+ due to his size, he can get pretty wiggly when he is excited! Klint was mistreated by a man previously and can be a bit apprehensive around new men and needs time to warm up and build trust. Once he has it, he is as loyal as they come.

He would like to be the only pet and he does not enjoy the company of cats or other small critters. Klint is neutered, UTD on his shots and micro-chipped. His adoption fee is $200.00.

animal.description:
Humane Society/SPCA of Nelson County - ALMOST HOME

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

Phone: 434 263-7722
Email: pets@nelsonspca.org

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

YOU MUST READ VERY TOUCHING STORY!!! VIDEO!!!UPDATE 7/28/2020:
Kilburn, an Australian Shepherd (mix), and Jasmine (a Beagle) came to us on 7/5/19, after their owner (a generous supporter of Almost Home) passed away. Both dogs were terribly overweight. Little Jasmine was quickly adopted but Kilburn didn't share her same luck. When Kilburn arrived, he was 5 years old, weighed 106 pounds, and seemed depressed from all the drastic life changes in his life. But once he got to know us and learn we were friends, he begged for belly rubs and gave us his trademark, full-face Kilburn smile. He is now 6 years old and weighs a healthy 57 pounds-he has lost half his body weight. (Kilburn's birthday is 11/8/13. He looked like a little bear when he was born.)
He seemed on his way to find happiness, when suddenly his rear legs gave out. We were afraid for him. The diagnosis was that he'd had a bout of FCE ( https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/fibrocartilaginous-embolusemboli-fce-in-dogs ). Luckily, he recovered as if nothing ever happened, and Veterinarians say it is rarely recurrent. This is great news and his legs have been working great since that event.
The much thinner Kilburn is quite perky and his handsome face and happy brown eyes hide the loss he endured a year ago. He is more than ready for a home of his own now. Who can resist that waggling bob-tail that makes him look as if a black and tan teddy-bear came alive? Sometimes, he will even stretch a paw out to get you to notice him. He loves to be brushed too.
Kilburn has tried new homes twice but was returned because he tried to protect things he was afraid would be taken away. He let folks know he thought food was too yummy to share. He also tried to explain that he was picky about dogs he might need to live with. He might prefer to just live with his people and be the most important to them.
This poor dog has suffered so much loss in such a short time, he needs someone to let him know that he doesn't need to lose anything more. He loves a belly rub or a good scratch of the butt and may back right up into your hand to get one. He also loves to chase and retrieve squeak toys. He enjoys easy leash walks and is a good listener if you want to sit and talk. Kilburn keeps his room clean (an indication he is housed trained and/or would be easy to be) and like us can't resist a good nap in his own comfy bed.
While he is in his dream world, we imagine he sees himself in a calm household with people who are understanding and want to share their hearts with his. He would do best in a home without children and/or children that visit.VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org

animal.description:
The Davey days of summer are here ??
This 5 year old brindle beauty may be a work in progress but he is worth it. He loves to go on long walks, play ball, and curl up with a good chew toy. He is a high energy dog so a yard is a plus for Davey. After exercising he settles down for a nice massage and a peanut butter kong. We are currently looking for an experienced foster with no other dogs Initially in the NYC area. We will provide Davey’s foster hero with everything needed to care for him.

We rescued Davey from ACC after a good samaritan found him laying on a busy road here in Queens. He was emaciated and suffered trauma resulting in a fractured pelvis, completely split lip, and cuts and scrapes.

When we pulled Davey to safety his first stop was our orthopedic surgeon and primary vet for medical care. After 6 weeks with us his body had healed but he still had some emotional healing to do so we teamed up with one of our trusted trainers who has worked extensively with Davey on basic commands, manners, impulse control and leash work. We are excited for Davey’s future. To help make his dreams come true apply at Zionsmission.org

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org

Meet Sandy Mae! She's a gracious, senior lady standard dachshund mix. While we don't know her back story, she's obviously had a loving home at one time. She came in spayed, heartworm negative, and completely house trained.

Sandy is in the early stages of dog dementia or CCD - Canine Cognitive Dysfunction. But don't let that concern you, she is a wonderful, sweet, and calm pup! She recognizes her foster family and is happy to meet new people. She follows her family around and hangs out where her foster sibling dogs are. She loves taking naps in her dog bed and keeps herself busy with kongs and exploring the house.

She gets along with dogs - big and small - and doesn't mind the cat either. She explores the foster home often and is always wanting to be where you are. She doesn't bolt out the door and will stay by your side when outside. She doesn't care too much for toys, but will look longingly into your eyes for treats!

If you would like to meet this beautiful lady, she can be seen at various adoption events around San Antonio or schedule a meet and greet! If you would like to sponsor her while she waits for her forever home, please click the Sponsor This Pet button above.

PUPDATE: Sandy Mae is doing well. She loves to hang out with her foster family and is a wonderful help around the house! She perks up when going for walks and gets a bounce in her step. Nighttime can be a little confusing for her, but once she sees her humans, she relaxes and will drift back to sleep.

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

DOB: 4/30/2015
Weight:  88 lbs

Hi! I'm Atlas, a staffi/ lab mix. I am 5 years old. Here is my story: 
I originally lived in a home with another dog and small children. I didn't really mind the other dog for the most part, but I didn't like the little child constantly messing with my food, toys, and in my face. I started growling and becoming aggressive. From that point on, I developed food and toy aggression. It's been a work in progress, but I still have ways to go with it. I was surrendered for that reason, other than that- I did great with the child. I would be okay in a home with children who understand personal space and not make me feel cornered even though I am 85+lbs- so older kids. I would be great in a home where my owners understood my developed aggression and continued to help me improve. I know I look intimidating, but the reality is, I'm confused and not really sure why I ended up here. Most people overlook me because I look "scary". I am really just a big happy go lucky baby. Some things I do love: cuddling, trying to be a lap dog even though I'm way too big, and treats!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thank you for your interest in adopting one of our foster animals! The first step in the adoption process is submitting an application. Please visit our website for more information and a link to the application: www.kgarl.org/info/adoption
Jesse is a very special girl, who is looking for her forever home. She was found as a stray and ended up at King George Animal Control, from there, she was pulled by the King George Animal Rescue League (KGARL). Jesse is currently in a foster home and is doing very well. She loves to play with the other dogs in the home but in the evenings, she's content to take a nap on the couch.

Jesse is very smart and very food motivated. She learned "sit" and "down" within minutes of arriving at her foster home. Jesse has some issues with possessiveness, which is very well managed with consistent rules. She needs an owner who is willing to continue working with her.

If you think Jesse is the dog for you, please submit an application at www.kgarl.org/adoptAdoption process

Once your application is received, the application process begins. We will review your application, check your references, check with your vet (if there are other animals in the household), speak to a landlord (if you rent), and arrange for a home visit.

Submitting an application does not guarantee a specific dog or cat. We strive to match the personality and needs of our foster dogs and cats to a family who will best fulfill those needs. If a family is not approved for a particular pet, it does not mean they will not be a good pet owner, it just means that their needs and the needs of the particular pet don't match. We do not adopt on a "first come, first serve" basis.

Please note that we do not do same day adoptions. If you are applying for a popular animal (such as puppies, small dogs, or special breeds), it can take several days for our volunteers to reach a decision that is best for the animal. We understand that it's difficult to wait, but please don't email us multiple times a day to check on the status of your application. We are a very small group and the same people that are reviewing your application are also replying to hundreds of emails and facebook messages. We are all volunteers and have full time jobs outside of KGARL, so any time spent replying to emails/messages is time we are not reviewing your application.

Once your application is pre-approved (meaning, we don't see any red flags based on our preliminary review of your application), the applicant may be invited to meet their potential family member at a location convenient to the foster family (usually at the King George Petco). Adoptions will NOT take place at the meet & greet, this is just a chance for us to get to know you and for you to spend time with our animals. After the meet and greet, we will ask that you spend some time thinking over your decision and we will do the same.

After the application review process is complete (meet & greet with animal, home visit, reference/vet checks, background check, etc.), if all is acceptable to both adopter and KGARL and we all agree to move forward, we will schedule a day/time to finalize the adoption. The adopter will be asked to sign the final paperwork and we will collect the adoption fee (cash, check, or paypal are all acceptable). At this time, you can either pick up your pet, or schedule a time to do so. Adopters will be required to schedule an appointment with their veterinarian of choice within 10 days of taking your new pet home.

All Adoptions Include:

Lifetime of free advice from KGARL!

Spayed or Neutered Pet

Heartworm, FIV, Feline Leukemia Testing

Complete medical records

Up to date on core vaccines

On Flea/Tick Preventative

Microchipped

Sample of Pet Food

Adoption Fees (unless otherwise noted in the pet's description):

Special Breeds of Dogs: See pet's description
Puppies: $400
Adult Dogs : $350
Adult Hounds and Beagles: $250
Kittens: $125
Adult Cats: $100

animal.description: Dobbie (not named by us, of course) came to us from an animal shelter where he had been deemed "rescue only" because he failed a temperament test on his dog-to-dog interaction on leash. What we're hoping for is a home where his new owner will not have small kids or other animals, but where Dobbie may have visits from the owner's grandchildren or neighbor children. We think it's sad that shelters are making our judgment calls for us on dogs' suitability for certain homes when they really don't know our breed! A majority of our dogs can be reactive to other dogs when on leash. Anyway, Dobbie is strong, so he'll need work on leash, and he's also been only an outside dog, so he'll need to learn house manners also. He's about 5 years old and he's a big boy; about 90 pounds.

animal.description:
Rockford is an incredibly precious boy with the moist ridiculously adorable mug!  and like a few of our other dogs, highly perceptive... he watches and feels everything!
 
 He likely was born with a keen awareness of his environment but we also feel certain his early life experience honed his acutely perceptive nature. What this means in Rockfords case is he will understand what your breath is saying! It's an incredible gift actually to be able to share communication with a dog like Rockford.

WE so love seeing this sweet chocolate brindle boy be relaxed and content & so unlike the petrified puppy who arrived to us with burned skin, thin, wormy and sickly!

?Rockford has always come to life in the company of other dogs and we have used that to help him find HIS way to befriending people.. Rockford is a dog that will require dedication and loyalty.. he doesn't trust new people easily, not in an  aggressive way, just so incredibly reserved. Life has told him that is the way to keep himself safe.. Once in Rockford's trust circle, it is so rewarding to watch his layers unfold!! 

For more info on Rockford and his journey, visit our website.. better yet, fill out an application to come give this darling a boy a chance! 

***While we are very grateful for PetFinder, we have been having chronic problems receiving inquires. Please contact us directly if you are interested in adopting by emailing us at lovedogs.bedfordny@gmail.com and visit fortheloveofdogsrescue.org***

animal.description:
Leia was born around November 13, 2018.

Leia was living in a home with Chloe, but they were surrendered to a high-kill shelter because their owners could no longer afford to keep them.  Leia is affectionate and always aware of her surroundings -- she doesn't miss anything!  Whether Leia is having a chat with you or letting you know she sees something that she thinks requires your attention, you'll always know what's going on.

Leia does well crated -- she settles down and keeps it clean.  When crated during adoption events, she barks at other dogs when they approach the crate.  Dogs often do this simply because they're confined and feel the other dog is encroaching in their space.

Leia would do best as a single dog in the household and should not go to dog parks, etc., since she is selective on who she considers a potential friend.  A fenced yard is necessary for Leia and unless it is a privacy fence, there should be space between the neighbor's fence to alleviate negative "fence play".

Leia weighs 46 pounds, she is spayed, on heartworm and flea preventative and she is microchipped.
 
ADOPTION EVENTS -- Meet some of our available dogs and cats on the 1st Saturday of each month at the Avon PetSmart (noon to 2:30 pm)

**SCHEDULE A SPECIAL MEET AND GREET**
Submit an application to set up a meet and greet during the week, evenings, and other Saturdays throughout the month.

Application, Costs, and Procedure
Please email us to request an application. It contains details about the adoption fee and other information about the adoption process. You can also visit our website at arkfostercare.com and download an application.

Fax your completed application to 317-203-0722 or email it to: arkpets@hotmail.com

Questions can only be answered by email.

animal.description:
The only thing on my wish list this year is you! My name is Huckaby, the handsome pitty boy! I am a two year old, 67lb. guy. I am as smart as they come. I am house trained and know some cool tricks. I live for fetch but seem to forget to give it back after you throw it! I am needing a privacy fenced yard to stretch these legs, so no apartment life for me! I am working hard on leash training. I will have it down in no time though. I am great with older kids and other dogs. Another high energy dog in my forever home would be fabulous! Fill out an application and we will be rocking this forever life together in no time! 


My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
I can co-exist with dogs of all sizes, and boy, do I love my walkies.
My tongue is permanently sideways, no idea why but all the humans around me say it's from an old injury. I am the messiest eater- so highly suggest either a Neater Feeder or someone who likes to clean my mess up daily :)
*Update 9-29-2020* September update on Mr. Coleman: He had a quiet summer after the first 4 months in his current foster home was spent mostly recovering from surgeries. We're still monitoring his cancer, he's got several new lumps that are being monitored but were still too small for the U to be able to get samples to test for cancer. The large tumor that was removed is not showing any significant signs of regrowth so that is really good news!

He does still battle pretty severe separation anxiety (covid has not helped this as the foster human now works from home full time so the work previously done with him on easing this anxiety has been mostly undone by the fact he's rarely alone now). He would do best in a home where his humans can be home most of the time.
We have made quite a bit of progress on his car anxiety. For long rides we are giving him CBD to help him calm down some as he can no longer take trazadone due to adverse reactions post-op. Now that he knows not all car rides end up in a new home or at the vet he seems to not be as stressed. He likely will have some regression here during the transition to a new home, but it's great to see he doesn't always hate car rides!
Over the course of summer we've learned he really only likes walks on his terms and will occasionally protest them by trying to turn around and return home as soon as he does his business. However, regular slow walks are good for his hips/knees and to keep him slim!
Coleman will tolerate small humans but a quieter home is definitely preferable as he's very scared of loud noises, yelling (whether directed at him or not) makes him very nervous and he will cower if he hears yelling. He does do well with most other dogs & likes to play in very small bursts and not daily! He's a lazy old man at heart so prefers to snooze on the couch and get pets over too much physical activity. Stairs are still a problem, he panics, so a home with limited stairs is still best for him.
Coleman would make a great addition to the right family!

*Update 5-23-2020* Coleman is so excited to share that he's been given the all clear to resume regular activity, including walks and hot laps around his foster human's backyard! Friday was a really good day for Coleman! He has to build to full activity to ensure no set backs from his surgical incision but things are looking very good two months post op.

As a reminder, Coleman is available for adoption but does come with a few special needs. Coleman does have cancer, we've removed as much of the tumor as possible off his back leg with two surgeries but his furever home should know it will likely grow back and the U of M Oncology department does recommend keeping an eye on it for quality of life purposes. He also has a large tooth that will need to be extracted but he needs a break from surgeries for awhile.
Coleman also can't go to a home with stairs he would need to do daily. Both his last foster home and current have noticed similar issues, he's scared of them and he will slip and trip on them. One or two to go outside is fine, but a full set or split level set is out. Too risky for this old fella! A fenced in backyard is also preferred as he had some bathroom issues at his last foster who did not have a fenced in yard, but he's done well in his current foster home after settling in!
Coleman does have separation anxiety as well. He was making progress there before his surgery but he would do best in a quiet home with his people there most of the time. He's been a very big fan of the fact his foster human is working remotely indefinitely.
Overall Coleman is a great dog who has some medical needs and is the messiest eater and drinker ever! He's got a lot of spunk left and loves joining in on walks and playtime, but does run out of energy fast during play time! He loves naps on the couch by the human and also firmly believes the human's bed is his own.
*Update 3-23-2020*
Coleman is back at the U for his next surgery. At his Oncology consult they too recommended we try to remove the remaining tumor and gave us a less invasive option that should hopefully still be very successful. He is otherwise a very healthy boy for his age so MNBR decided to move ahead with this surgery. His tumor was continuing to grow quite rapidly, so over time it would cause him quality of life issues due to the lack of skin on his leg, especially since so much was removed during his first surgery.
While the U is on a reduced surgery schedule and only doing emergency cases they agreed that fitting Coleman in ASAP was important to get the surgery done before the cancer grew/spread any further.
His foster mom asks you all send him some positive thoughts tonight, as it's his first night away from her and with his anxiety it will be hard on him, and especially tomorrow morning during surgery. We won't know the full scope of what they will remove until they are in there but Coleman could very likely end up with a flap and a drain and a month of sutures so he's in for a rough couple of weeks. He healed really well last time, even after busting a couple of stitches, so hoping this will repeat and we'll be taking advantage of his foster mom's temporary COVID remote working schedule to get him up and running again. Once he recovers he will go off medical hold and we'll start working on finding his perfect family! He'll need an understanding family who gets he's always going to make a mess when he eats and drinks, that he'll slobber all over the place always since his tongue is always out and he really needs a family who is home all the time or almost all the time. We've worked on his anxiety but for him to thrive he'll do best having his people with him as much as possible!
We'll provide an update once he's back home!
*Update 2-15-2020*
We got his test results back yesterday and unfortunately two of his lumps came back as MCT's, neither of which have clean margins. One was the giant lump on his back thigh, the other was in his nubbin. I'll spare you the details but the giant one appears that it is not able to be removed without drastic measures that are not in Coleman's best interests. We do have a follow up appointment scheduled in two weeks to determine what his path forward looks like and get a second set of eyes on his test results.
He is doing good after the stitch fiasco and his wrist is looking better. He's going to get lots of love and spoiling over the next two weeks and then we will determine what is next for Coleman . All positive thoughts for him will be much appreciated!
*Update 2-9-20*
I got all a mouth lift recently, along with some lumps and bumps removed, which means I get to wear a sexy e-collar and bodysuit, but I promise my sweetness and personality were not removed with the lumps.
I am settling into my third foster family as I struggle with Separation Anxiety and am slowly learning that my foster mom CAN leave the house and that she will return, but it's a process. I will need a plastic crate as it keeps me safe and a lot of Kongs filled with goodies.
I can co-exist with dogs of all sizes, and boy, do I love my walkies.
My tongue is permanently sideways, no idea why but all the humans around me say it's from an old injury. I am the messiest eater- so highly suggest either a Neater Feeder or someone who likes to clean my mess up daily :)
I accept donations for my surgery! Cash, PayPal or Treats, your choice!

animal.description:
Date of birth: 10/2016

12/17/2020: Marvin is a handsome 4 year old Pit Bull mix. He is very, very sweet and friendly and he loves to please people.  He loves peanut butter Kongs and stuffed toys! He enjoys going on pack walks.  He's a smart boy, too!

• Marvin gets along with some other dogs. He does best with dogs who aren’t bossy— he likes to be the boss. If you have a dog who needs a bossy guy, you could make an appointment to bring your dog in to meet Marvin to see if they could be buddies. 

• We think a yard with a wooden privacy fence would be best for him.

• He’d be good with teenage kids, but not young kids— he’s a big strong guy and a bit of a bulldozer! 

• He has a prey drive so he needs a home without cats.  

• That said, be sure to check out the video we posted of Marvin meeting a frog! Marvin wasn't sure what to think about his new friend. (No amphibians were injured in the process!)

• Marvin was picked up by KCK Animal Services as a stray. The poor guy was emaciated, the flies had bitten up his ears and he had heartworms. We transferred Marvin to our care to get him healthy. He now weighs about 60 lbs, up from 48 lbs. He loves to eat and he’s very food motivated. He’s actually on a diet now because he’s gotten chunky! He has completed heartworm treatment and is heartworm free now.  

• Marvin has been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. He’s had a rough life, but he’s a sweetheart and now he deserves a loving home!

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
http://hsgkc.org

animal.description:
Kam prefers to be in a quiet household where he can be with his human. He is not a cuddle bug but must be near his person at all times. He can get testy around food and other getting between him and his person but will back down after he lets out a warning. He is not a fan of bigger dogs. We, also think he would be better without young children and all their activities. Kam is not housebroken but tolerates belly bands. He is on a routine in his foster home and is doing well but well still have a few accidents.

Kam has been on Petfinders for awhile with his best friend Kip.  They came to us several years ago as strays and were adopted by a wonderful couple.  Over the years their adoptive mom passed away and their dad got to the point where he could not care for them.  So they were returned to the group as our contract says.  Recently Kip has crossed over the Rainbow Bridge when his heart could not continue.  We had planned to keep them together.  Kam misses his friend but is doing well by himself. 

Kam is a sweet boy.  He has had a rough life before he had come to us the first time.  We are not sure what the boys went through but we have promised that their life will be wonderful from the day we received them.

Kam is an older dog.  We are not sure of the age but he is at least eight years old.  Something has happened to his back end so he does not wag his tail.  His back end will give way while he is walking.  He rolls his paws while he is walking.  But he gets to where he needs to go and quickly if he has to.  He is on pain medicine for  his arthritis and it seems to be under control.

He did develop an eye infection that we treated very aggressively and it was not improving.  It became clear that he was in a great deal of pain.  We had the eye removed and he has not missed it.  He feels better and is feisty like normal.

Kam prefers to be in a quiet household where he can be with his human.  He is not a cuddle bug but must be near his person at all times.  He can get testy around food and other getting between him and his person but will back down after he lets out a warning.  He is not a fan of bigger dogs.  We, also think he would be better without young children and all their activities.  Kam is not housebroken but tolerates belly bands.  He is on a routine in his foster home and is doing well but well still have a few accidents.

Kam is a special boy with his querks and he deserves a wonderful loving forever home.  If you have room in your heart for this guy let us know.
 
If interested in giving Kam a home, please complete an application at www.safeanimalhaven.com

animal.special_needs_notes:
Being a bit wobbly doesn't hold her back at all!
 

WHY SPECIAL NEEDS:
Sweet Melody has ataxia.  There are three types of ataxia. It is sensory ataxia that fits her symptoms most closely. Her back legs cause her to wobble when she walks and when she runs. But, this little dog is not held back by this disability at all. She runs and plays with other dogs and people with no issue! 
Hey, what's the big deal if her bum wobbles from side to side a little bit?!

Sensory ataxia in dogs is linked to problems with the spinal cord, so the most common symptoms are related to loss of balance and an awkward or unbalanced gait. Some potential causes for this type of ataxia include a structural or developmental abnormality in the spinal cord, tumors of the spine, infection in the vertebrae, inflammation or trauma of the spinal cord, or a medical condition called degenerative myelopathy. Other symptoms of sensory ataxia include misplacing the feet and progressive weakness.

animal.description:
Bella is approximately 6 years old.
It's hard to believe and incredibly heartbreaking to know that these pictures are of our same little Bella, who came back into rescue August of 2019. Little did we know then that her issues may have been related to what we learned now to be Masticatory Muscle Myositis with possible underlying events of sporadic seizures. Bella will most likely need to be on prednisone for most of her life. A life we hope one day will find her back in a home that will  love her no matter what she looks like. Like the others currently in boarding, we pray she finds a home that will work for her. One where she can be the only fur-kid to be doted on. Bella needs a home with a secured fenced yard with privacy panels and a responsible owner as she can be animal reactive.
Shes rather small but very active and strong so an experienced handler is necessary. 

* In order to process only serious applicants,  please note  that all animals shown on this pet finder site have not yet been officially adopted. Inquiries asking if the animal is available will not be addressed . Requesting "more information" without being specific will also not be addressed. *


Due to limited resources, we can only place Bella in the Omaha area or within a 30 mile radius

animal.description:
Sunbeams, seasonal fruits, chairs for exactly 1 (her), and long walks on secluded beaches: these are a few of Peaky’s favorite things. She’s the perfect COVID companion--she strongly prefers 6 feet from strangers and likes to keep the houseguests to members of the pod. Shaking hands and kissing babies may not be her jam, but if you’re a Real One, Peaky’s happy to lounge the day away as your sophisticated sidekick. With time, she’ll start to dole out her patented Peaky Pecks (the teeniest kisses) and press herself next to you on the couch. 

Peaky has a great low to flexible energy level and is quite satisfied with a neighborhood meander with plenty of time budgeted for sniffing (in her opinion, if you wanted to get your heart rate up, you should go for a run). She’s happy to throw in a special hike or adventure here or there--in fact, her favorite foster outing is to share a breakfast burrito and play in the waves on a quiet beach. From there, she’ll happily entertain herself with a sunbeam nap, a chew on a bone, or an occasional spurt of silliness or a formidable game of tug. When you’re gone, a crate full of cozy blankets is all she needs to content herself. 

Peaky’s occasional cat-like independence seems to come from a place of being an introverted worrywart. She’s been working hard in her foster home to learn new skills to lift the weight of the world off her shoulders. She considers herself a high maintenance low maintenance dog--really, all she needs is a comfy place to rest her head, share a snack, and keep up with her pesky allergies (did she mention she is quite literally allergic to people?!), and the rest of her sometimes silly, sometimes sweet, always quirky personality will reveal itself in time. 

Check out more from Peaky on her Instagram at @particularly.peaky (https://www.instagram.com/particularly.peaky/)

About 4.5 years old and 55 pounds, Peaky is crate-trained, house-trained, micro-chipped, up to date on routine vaccinations and knows her basic commands.

animal.description:
My name is Harley, and I'm looking for my forever home!

My rescue friends say I am a volunteer favorite because I am such a happy, playful guy who makes everyone smile! They say I am lots of fun and that I love to cuddle, too.  I love car rides, tummy rubs, and an occasional bath. My favorite game is playing ball, and the rest of the time I am just happy to hang out with people.

I love my walks and am learning to walk nicely without pulling, and I know some basic commands. I’m housebroken and I rarely bark. 

I love everyone I meet, but I have to admit that young children can make me a little nervous. I met a really cool hamster in one of my foster homes, but I still haven’t figured out cats. I have gone on lots of pack walks with other dogs and participated in several large dog playgroups. I liked some of the dogs and didn’t get along with others…I guess you could say that I’m dog selective and would be happier if I was your one and only pup.

I live in a foster home now, and I love my crate and my toys. I'm a good boy when my foster mom is at work. Sometimes she takes me to work with her and I love hanging out there, and meeting all the people!

Harley is 8-years-old, neutered, microchipped and up-to-date with shots.

animal.description:
Holy legs Turkey man! 

This handsome fella is Turkey and is a 2 year old Hound/Shepard mix (best guess). Turkey was returned to the shelter in March of this year after he started showing signs of resource guarding. Since being at the shelter, Turkey's people have been taking every chance they get to work on "what's mine is your's" with him to allow him to be the very best boy! Turkey loves to run in the play yard and walks fairly well on his leash when he is being taken out by staff members. 

Turkey will thrive best with an active family who can provide daily runs and weekend hikes! A new family for our Turkey will also need time and patience available to devote to exercise, training and socialization. Turkey will sit for his treats, but tends to guard his food. Turkey is seeking an adult only home with no kiddos in the home or visiting the home due to guarding. He will need an owner committed to having no dog toys or high value items in the home. 

Turkey will need a family without feline friends or small animal critters in the house due to his high prey drive. Dog siblings will be dependent on a meet and greet basis. Following adoption, staff highly recommends waiting at least 4 weeks until working on outside of household introductions. An owner with experience with behavioral / guarding issues is highly recommended. 

If interested in adopting Turkey, please visit www.lebanonhumane.org for all the details on our current adoption process.
