animal.description: Noel will make your holidays merry and bright! At just 2 years old, Noel found herself and her 6 tiny puppies homeless. She was a wonderful mother and her puppies all found loving homes, so now it's her turn to find a forever home all her own. A mix of Lab and Cattle Dog, Noel is an athletic and energetic young lady. Her foster family takes her on 3 runs or walks a day, but she wouldn't complain if it was more often or for longer each time. Her forever family needs to be dedicated to getting her plenty of mental and physical stimulation each day. The world wasn't very kind to Noel in the first few years of her life, so she's nervous when meeting new people. She's working on building her confidence in her foster home and is looking for a kind and patient forever family ready to help her learn to trust again. Younger children make her nervous and we think she'd be happiest in a home with no children or only older, respectful children. She's fostered with other dogs and loves to romp and play with them in the family yard. Noel would love another dog in her forever home and she is good meeting new dogs that come over to her foster home. Noel is both house and crate trained, and she sleeps through the night on her foster parents' bed. She has just started to play with toys and is an absolute lovebug with her humans. If you are interested in giving Noel a home for a holidays, your first step is to submit an adoption application on our website. If you are already approved with a coach or have adopted from us before, reach out to your coach for the next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

ADOPTION DONATION: $800 (for Lyn-Z and Dare)
HEALTH: LYN-Z IS BLIND. She is spayed, microchipped, flea treated, dewormed, and is current on vaccines. Your adoption donation goes toward the cost of this vet care as well as other incidental costs of care.

HISTORY: Lyn-Z came to us from our friends in Texas. Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find Lyn-Z a great forever family!

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: LYN-Z is a wonderful girl. Blind dogs see with their heart. Or something along those lines. I think Lyn-Z heard this in a Hallmark movie or something. So she takes that to "heart,"

She is sweet and affectionate. Everything you could ask for in a pup. She does require another dog in the home, and has bonded for life with her BFF bulldog/pitbull mix, Dare. He's also her ESA and helps her when she gets anxious in new places. Blind dogs do best with a dog companion. She does have some separation anxiety which is why she requires another dog. You wouldn't know it until you take Dare out of the picture as she's quite content as long as he's around. And she can be a little nervous in new places. She is crate trained and sleeps in her crate at night. She can play a little rough with small dogs as she can't see their corrections. She's great with dogs of all ages and can wrestle with the puppies and sleep with the elderly. She is learning not to jump, since blind dogs see with their paws and nose, they tend to jump on people in greeting for touch and smell. Like Olaf she loves warm hugs! She will need to learn new commands such as Wall, Step, etc. as will the adopter to help her navigate the world better. She's an excellent mapper but when walking the adopter needs to teach her commands so that she won't run into walls or trip over curbs and go up or down stairs, etc.

Unlike her BFF she can go to daycare where the other dogs can be monitored, as other dogs do not always appreciate blind dogs who can't see their cues. She's definitely not a dog park dog as we don't know how the other dogs will react to her and she could easily get hurt and unable to defend herself. She's a sensitive girl and the last thing you need is some bozo at the dog park hurting her feelings. Plus you can't bring Dare because he would tell that guy off and things would just go downhill from there. So no dog parks for this girl. But she's good with a fenced backyard for her to run circles in while barking at her imaginary friends (but we won't talk about that...).

She loves her people, and they are a source of comfort and affection for her. She will trust you explicitly and greets you with a hug. While she does entertain herself and take naps while you work, sometimes she will stop in for a quick hug and a kiss to reassure herself that you're there even though she can hear you clacking away at the keyboard or on your super important zoom meeting. She gives sweet kisses rather than the sloppy ones her BFF gives. With the two of them, expect many kisses. She's very tactile and touches you often, whether with her paws or body. She loves to climb in bed and snuggle with you at the end of the day and when she's done playing with the other dogs, but more of a puppy piler type then spooner.

She does love to be out and about, although hasn't learned to walk a straight line yet and looks like a drunk Lippizaner on a mission. Funny how she can't see yet feels she should be leading... She bounces off her BFF frequently while she prances down the trail but he doesn't mind. She will definitely "see" the rabbit before anyone else. She loves the smells that come with walking on the trails.

Lyn-Z is a spunky sassy girl who loves to play. She loves to be in the backyard with the sun on her face and the mud under her feet. She's can be a talker when she's nervous. As she's blind she hears a lot and isn't always a fan of dogs on the TV or youtube videos, as she will grumble and bark back at them. You talkin' to me?! She'll leave the room if you're watching a horror flick because creepy music... ch, ch, ch, ah, ah, ah!

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and Martingale collar (or a harness, if necessary), depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO:
Motley Zoo Animal Rescue is a volunteer run, foster based, 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization based in Redmond, WA. Motley Zoo does not have a traditional shelter location, but instead, utilizes private foster homes which care for the animals individually, in a home environment, until a "furever" home is found.

Motley Zoo also runs "Rock Star Treatment" Dog Daycare & Training Studio in Redmond, WA which is a day-use facility and does not hold kennels of adoptable animals. The dogs there are owned animals who come to the facility while their families are at work and school so they can play and socialize in a safe environment. We dub this service our "Year-round" fundraising program which helps us support our rescue animals and the $15,000/ month vet bills we incur. This Studio location does have an Adoptable Cat Lounge, where cats may live until adoption, which is the exception to any aforementioned rules.

Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application so we can get you started on the journey to finding a new, furry friend! Once you have been approved to adopt, then we can set up a meeting with the animal you have been matched with.

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

animal.description:
6/10/2020 On the verge of Sebastian's 1 yr birthday we want to update. Sebastian spent a little while in a foster to adopt situation. Everything was great until the foster mom started taking her small kids into the front yard to play while leaving Sebastian in the back yard alone. He started jumping the fence to be in the front yard with the family. Then when the family would put him outside alone he began jumping the fence and going to the front door so the adoption did not work out because the safety of Sebastian is our priority. Sebastian is a playful affectionate guy but he is timid in the beginning. He has separation anxiety and needs a companion and a home where he will be indoors when the family is at work. 

12/23/19 Update: Little Sebastian has made strides in the last few weeks. He is learning to be with other dogs, walk on a leash, his potty training is going well. He is a very snuggly, playful dog. 

Started the morning out trying to save a 6 month old German Shepherd boy with a broken leg from the local kill shelter. He had been hit by a car, animal control took him to vet. Owner was contacted but she never went to pick him up so he was taken to the kill shelter where he sat in a crate. He has demodectic mange so we are treating that too and will take him back next to to check leg again and get him neutered then he can get stitches and cast off at same time.

He's not socialized so we'll be working on that, house manners and basic obedience!!  

He has 2 more weeks in the cast and then if all goes well he will be official available for adoption. 12/1/19

IN VERMONT

Meet Lucas! Here is his video in NC:
https://youtu.be/jGQvtyPeVU8

Lucas 5 years old (approx. DOB 10-30-15), male, 51 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Shelter staff said Lucas loves belly rubs! Lucas loves to run, play with his ball (as in the video), and is a very happy bubbly boy! He came into the shelter in bad shape; very emaciated as you can see from the pictures below. Although at the shelter Lucas met a similar large female terrier and did fine. He was very energetic, but showed no sign of reactions towards her. However he did not do well with another male that he met at boarding. Lucas will do best in a home without other dogs, in a rural setting, and with an experienced family. From his VT Foster family: Lucas is good with dog friends with proper introduction; doesn't like cats, but loves humans of all ages (does very well with children.....and horses!). He is crate trained, potty trained and has no sign of separation anxiety. Lucas loves his walks/hikes and does well on leash, still a bit afraid of loud traffic but working on his confidence. He knows some basic commands such as Sit, Off and Leave It. Lucas is very sweet and loving; very easy going. Stay tuned for more information as Lucas is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Lucas please fill out an Application at
www.Passion-4-Paws.org
(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description: Apollo is a 9ish year old loving and sweet boy, but he has a few things going on with him, and one is he has laryngeal paralysis which causes him to sound somewhat like a lion.  Apollo is also missing his spleen because he had a benign tumor which needed removal, and since the tumor was wrapped around his spleen our vet had to take his spleen to remove the tumor.  Recently Apollo had a growth removed from his toe which turned out to be a low-grade Mast Cell Cancer.  Apollo needs a safe fenced yard because he cannot be walked on a leash and collar, due his laryngeal paralysis.  If he is pulled too hard he will actually lose air and pass out.  Apollo he can be managed on a harness, but even that causes him discomfort.   Apollo is fully vetted including a full dental and blood work up.  He doesn't appear to have any issues with other dogs, but we are seeking an only pet home for Apollo because he has been at our shelter for more than a year now and he will need time to decompress.  ??

animal.description:
This girl is around 5 years old and about 60 lbs. Samantha has an amazing rescue story, she was living and surviving all on her own behind the abandoned Jack in the Box for almost 3 YEARS, she was so afraid and living in survival mode. But we never gave up and after years of feeding her she finally succumbed to allowing herself be touched. Samantha has done awesome in her foster home. She loves ALL dogs and she has a very submissive attitude. She would probably be most comfortable in a home with older kids or no kids. Samantha is great in a crate and she regards her crate as her safe place. She loves to snuggle on the bed and adapts very well when she has a routine to follow. Samantha would love a happily ever after, she is up to date on all shots and preventative, spayed and ready for a home. Her adoption fee is only $95, please let us know if you would like to be part of real rescues life.
Our Samantha has been with us over a year. On June 21st, 2019 after months of tirelessly trying to catch her. We finally did! She is shy but wants someone to love her and give her a forever home for her remaining years. She needs a home that understands the trauma she’s endured. She needs someone to show her that it’s okay to trust humans. She loves other dogs but would probably prefer a home without small children due to her shyness. *see this sweet dolls current glamour shots and past photos from how she was living on her own before Rufus Refuge found her*
From June 21, 2019. After being on her own and living out behind the abandoned ‘jack in the box’ for almost 3 years- she is now safe.  Samatha wanted badly to trust- she was just too afraid. we will never know how she got out there but obviously a very smart girl to survive on her own that long.  
After several hours of talking to her, she finally surrendered to being touched. She decided maybe “all” humans aren’t so bad.
It’s been a long hard road for Samantha - she will need some down time to just chill and get used to her new human interaction. She is so sweet and is going to make somebody a fabulous companion!!

animal.description:
HI THERE!
We are Saving Pets At Risk (SPAR) and we really appreciate you stopping by! We are crazy about our rescues and we are confident you will fall in love, too! Following us on Facebook is a great way to find out what we are up to. 
https://www.facebook.com/SPARShawnee/

MEET BETSY AND YOU'LL FALL IN LOVE! 
She pals around with her long time dog friends, Benson and Kimmy! She is certainly motivated by treats, barks at first then settles right down once she meets the company/visitors.

BETSY
-- This lovely, senior lady is 9-years-old (as of 2020)
-- Mixed breed (part Black Lab)
-- Mid-length coat, shiny black
-- Spayed
-- House-broken/house trained
-- Leash trained
-- Travels well in a car
-- Enjoys playing with most dogs. This is especially true of her buds, Benson and 
     Kimmy, with whom she's been living with for many years. They are also 
     available for adoption.
-- Microchipped
-- Current on vaccinations/shots
-- Heartworm preventative (heartworm negative)
-- Flea/tick preventative
-- Playful, smart, strong, energetic, funny, & loves to play in the water.
-- Good-natured, sweet disposition, gentle
-- Older Children - Good fit
-- Other Dogs - Good fit
-- Cats - Unknown

APPLICATION PROCESS:
To help us ensure the best forever-match for our rescues and adopters, we require the following:
-- Completed & submit an adoption application.
-- Phone interview
-- Meet and greet with the rescue dog.
-- Compatibility testing by SPAR to ensure the applicant's pets get along with 
     our rescue.
-- Home visits conducted prior to adoption.

QUESTIONS:
If you'd like to meet Betsy, this is how to contact us:
-- Complete and submit an adoption application first.
-- email: SPARpets@gmail.com.
-- Contact us via Petfinder.
-- Text or call Sherry today at 405.641.7831 (leave detailed information.)
      or
-- Text or call Phyllis today at 405.826.2917 (leave detailed information.)
-- We will return contact, usually within two days. (Rescuing dogs keeps us 
     busy!)

SPAR REQUIREMENTS:
-- Fenced yard
-- SPAR Dogs must reside indoors, living as part of the family, in the home.

animal.description:
Hi my name is PABLO.  I am a red 8 yr old male retired racing greyhound.  My official name is Mulbury Lazboy, but my former parents called me Pablo.  I was living in a home for several years but because of their health, they could no longer care for me.  I have now been rehomed to Michigan in a wonderful foster home.  I do not get on furniture or beds.  I sleep on my comfy dog beds.  I need rugs to walk on wood floors.  I can not live with small dogs and cats, but I do live with 1 other greyhound and 2 pitties.  I love to talk.  I get a little noisy when you come home from work/shopping.  I get so excited that I run and grab my bed and want to drag it around.  I am a very quiet boy until you get on the phone.  Then I want to talk along with you.  I use my talking roo voice.  I am very well behaved.  I am pretty much potty trained.  I can hold it about 5-6 hrs, if it is longer than that, I might have an accident.  I try my best.  I wake you up about 4 - 5am to tell you I need to go outside and go potty.  I eat 2 times a day.  I ride well in the car.  I sometimes need help getting into the truck.  I only do a few stairs going in and out of the house.  I can probably learn them easily though.  I am not a cuddly dog, I am very aloof and I don’t get in your way.  Are you the perfect home for me.  I would love to meet someone that would accept me as I am.  I will be your loyal best friend. 

Greyhound Expressions
greytluv@gmail.com

I love my hounds

animal.description:
Mr. Brown (aka King) is a super handsome, 1 yr old fawn cropped Cane Corso boy who was owner surrendered to a local animal control with his brother Stripes because they were escaping the yard and their owner wasn't interested in fixing the issue. King wasn't well socialized so being dumped at animal control was stressful for him however the shelter staff worked hard with him to build trust and made good progress. The shelter was affected by Tropical Storm Imelda and they were out of room for them both. King also needed more one on one so they reached out to us to help him and we are happy to do so. King is described as being laid back and generally calm, loud noises are a little scary for him. King's foster family will be working with this guy to help him learn about living indoors, basic commands and working on building his confidence and positive socialization. We can't wait to see this guy blossom and he's already relaxing and decompressing and we can update his bio once we get to know him a little more.

It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. animal.breeds_label: Catahoula Leopard Dog & Bluetick Coonhound Mix
animal.description:
** We ask that our potential adopters fill out an adopt application on our dogs first . No one is obligated by doing so but it is a first good step to see if they are a match. Our application can be found on our website www.jcldr.com

VERNON BRITISH COLUMBIA: Meet Boomer is a 9-year-old Catahoula /Treeing Walker/Bluetick Coonhound mix.. He is approximately 65 lbs at healthy weight, and he is neutered, HW negative (there is no heartworm where he lives, so he is not on preventative), up-to-date on vaccines, and microchipped. He is crate trained and very well housetrained, although he does mark outside like many male dogs. He has had a full dental cleaning and problem teeth extracted. Although he is still very active, Boomer is a senior working dog, and thus can overdo it and get a bit sore–this is easily managed, however, by making sure Boomer does not jump up or down from high places (like trucks), using a harness to walk him, and giving him age-appropriate supplements like glucosamine. Otherwise, he is in great shape for a large dog of his age and does not require medication.

HISTORY: Boomer came to us from a shelter in Idaho, where he was taken in as a stray along with a young pitbull he had been running the woods with for three weeks. The shelter posted him as a found dog, and were then notified by a woman who recognized the dog as belonging to her uncle, who had passed. The owner’s son had taken the dogs, but moved away and left them in the woods to fend for themselves. No other family members wanted the dogs, so Boomer spent six weeks at the shelter before we picked him up, passed over while his younger companion was adopted. It is clear that Boomer was a both a house pet and a hunting hound in his former life, and he is very happy to be in a warm, comfortable home again.

GOOD: Boomer is a wonderful dog, and quite ready to be a beloved pet. He gets along extremely well with medium and large size dogs of all kinds, and is gentle and affectionate with people. He does OK with small dogs as well, but can get a little overexcited with them. He backs off quickly if they get testy with him, however. He is very playful and is especially fond of balls and squeaky plush toys, which he throws and pounces on with vigor. He has plenty of pep and life left in him and can easily hike for an hour or two (on-leash only, see below), after which he snoozes soundly like the older dog he is. His tail is usually wagging, and he leans against his people gently to ask for pets and ear rubs. He greets strangers politely and with a wagging tail, also, even if they approach the vehicle he is in. He makes friends everywhere he goes with his handsome looks, soulful eyes, wagging tail and gentle temperament! Although many of our dogs in rescue do not make good dog park candidates, Boomer loves the *securely and fully fenced* dog park! He runs and plays with other dogs, gets pets from strangers, and makes everyone laugh with his baying. He would love to have another active, playful dog in his forever home to romp with! He is mostly calm and quiet at home, unless he wants to play, if he wants his dinner, or if another dog starts barking, in which case he will sing you a coonhound song. He is very responsive to verbal correction in the house, and learns quickly, though he does test his limits. He is docile being handled and lifted, and does not exhibit resource guarding behavior with humans or other dogs. Because he is highly food motivated, however, he can get a bit pushy getting into a smaller dog’s food dish (though still no growling or snapping), so he is fed in his crate while other dogs finish their meals. Boomer does fine at the vet and rides well in a car. He knows some basic commands (like sit, stay, and lay down), and he is eager to learn more for treats. With his food and toy motivation, coupled with his incredible hound nose, he would likely make an excellent trainee for competitive nosework, and his foster home has started him on scent tracking activities.

BAD: Boomer is a hound through and through, and we believe he was trained to hunt bears or cougars at one point. This means when he is out walking, his nose is to the ground, and if he catches a scent that interests him, he will pull and lunge to follow it with extreme focus. We are working on his leash manners, but he would not yet be a good fit for an adopter who is unsteady on his/her feet or lacks resistance strength. He is a large, strong, lean dog even at his age. When he catches bear/cougar scent especially, he bays and tries to take off after it. For this reason and because his recall is at this point unreliable, he will likely not be a good candidate for off-leash adventures and certainly cannot be left to roam in a fence-free yard. (Because of his age, a 5-foot wooden fence is fine. We are unsure if he would climb a chain-link.) With time and patience, we believe he can have nice leash manners, especially in a more suburban setting. His foster family is working hard on recall, leash manners, and redirecting his scent skills to a more appropriate activity for an older pet (like nosework). Also, he absolutely cannot be in a home with cats or other small animals – as a trained hunting hound, it is likely he will seriously injure or kill them. This is not a flaw, but exactly what he was bred and trained for. As mentioned above, he is kind and gentle with humans and other dogs… he is in no way a dangerous or mean dog. He is just a typical hunting hound with high prey drive. He also will follow his nose into trouble with counter-pillaging or trash-raiding when unsupervised, though he can’t jump fully up on a countertop (thankfully). His foster family is working to correct these behaviors and on obedience… in the meantime, he is crated when left home alone for safety.

UGLY: There is nothing ugly about Boomer. He is a sweet, loving, charming and intelligent dog ready for his retirement home.

animal.description:
Zion came to Horse Creek Wildlife on August 23, 2019 from the animal shelter. 

She is an ENERGETIC full-grown mixed breed weighing 30 pounds. She loves running and romping with other dogs in our fenced exercise areas.  She never meets a stranger and enjoys going for leash walks with our volunteers.

Zion will make a great new family member with the family that promises to love and care for her always!

All of our dogs are spayed or neutered and are current on all vaccinations. They are on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. All of their medical needs are taken care of before they are available for adoption. Our adoption fee is only $100.00. Please complete an application, if you have found a dog you are interested in adopting. You can find our application at www.horsecreekwildlife.org/applic.html. Once completed, you can forward it to adoptions@horsecreekwildlife.org or fax it to 731-926-3000. Kim Austin, our adoption facilitator, will be in contact with you as soon as she has an opportunity to review your application. Understand that she has other duties and she will not ignore any interest shown in adopting one of our dogs. An application will need to be approved before a scheduled time to visit our dogs will be set up.  It may take up to 48 hours before she returns your call or responds to your email, due to work schedules, holidays and adoption events. We do the very best we can for the dogs we have rescued and do not take the adoption process lightly. Please be patient and understand that we will place our rescued dogs in the very best homes possible and reserve the right to refuse applications.

animal.description:
Hi there! Coco here!  
I’m a real happy go lucky guy, a class clown if you will, but spending this much time in a loud shelter can be a bit stressful, as you can imagine. I would really love a home of my own where I could decompress. 

My favorite thing in the whole world is TOYS. I love toys, so much so that I ingest the pieces sometimes, and can guard them from my people. My shelter family makes sure I only get the real hardy toys that I can’t destroy and puts them up when they are interacting with me. I’m a strong boy, and my friends here at MLAR are teaching me manners and how to be the best dog I can be for my future family. Do you think you could continue my training in your home? 

I am anxious around new people so I must be introduced slowly and carefully. That will need to be done for every new person in my circle of friends and family. I also am very strong and get too excited over other dogs so I will need to go home as an only pet. I'm a funny guy who loves spending time outside in the play yards and entertaining my friends. If you'd like more information on me please fill out an application and our behavior manager will get back to you with more details.

If you are interested in meeting any of our adoptable dogs, please fill out an application at https://www.mlar.org/adoption-overview

E-mails regarding adoption are not considered an application. 

Out-of-state applicants (outside PA/NJ/DE) will not be considered, unless there are special circumstances. 

Please visit our web site for more detailed information on the animals in our care, our educational campaigns, and for helpful tips on adoption.  www.MLAR.org

animal.description:
Zeka and Zuri have been waiting since last September for a great home! The girls sure didn't have a great home in the past, and came to us in horrid condition when they were found together as strays. They're both around 8 years old and were skin and bones and covered in dirt when they came in. They spent time under medical care and it was discovered that Zeka (mostly gray face) had some mammary masses. They were removed but unfortunately, one of them was malignant, so that will always need to be watched in the future. Zeka also has some facial paralysis on one side but she doesn't let any of this stop her from being the biggest mush you've ever met. Her and Zuri both are incredibly sweet, loving, happy, well-behaved girls. Zuri is more playful and active, but they are both such fun, lovable girls. They will need a home with no other pets but they sure love each other. Zeka and Zuri hope you'll give them a chance! File#29182/83 9/19/19 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Zeka and Zuri.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description:
Hi! I’m Runa, a 5 year old Pit mix. I am looking for just the right person to take me in and love me. When I first meet people, I’m a little shy. Once I get a treat and some pets, my tail immediately starts wagging and I come back for more! It doesn't take me long at all to realize how awesome it is to be loved!

I don’t remember my previous life, but I don’t think I got much attention since I don’t immediately seek it out. All I need is someone to love me whom I can love back. I’ll be by your side and be your best friend forever!

I am super gentle when I take treats, I’m not jumpy or bark-y and would do great in a home with other dogs or kids. I got the chance to have a "meet-n-greet" with some lovely people and their dog. The doggie and I met and we had no problems deciding we were just fine with one another. After a minute or two of some quality attention with the humans, I was up giving them hugs and kisses. It was so nice! They also met a furry friend of mine and she got the grand prize for the day. It was a hard decision for them to make, but I know the right family will come along and pick me. (I am super happy for her, by the way.)

So if you have a spot in your home and heart for a sweet gal who could use some love, please come on out and meet me! You can contact the shelter at 972-382-3647 or email adoptionsmoh@gmail.com

I will be fully vetted before going to my new home.

animal.description:
Corpus Christi Animal Control was called by a citizen to come and retrieve an injured stray dog, and this was Ramona. She was in horrible condition and unable to use her back legs, which were rigid and unable to support her. Despite her condition, Ramona won the hearts of staff. We knew we had a wheelchair that would fit her (she doesn't need it anymore!), so we arranged for transport to Dallas and Ramona started her journey to wellness.

Despite her grim prognosis, with consistent care, treatment for her heartworm disease and rehabilitation, Ramona is the happy girl you see now. She's 100% housebroken and has her own room in the founder's home. She's now completely mobile, walks on her own and loves exploring outdoors. Ramona seems to prefer people to other dogs and can be too assertive to submissive dogs. She listens well and does what she's told. She can't be allowed on furniture or anything with height where she could jump down, as her rear end still walks by committee some days. She'll make an awesome companion for the right household; all she needs is that chance.

Rail thin and starving, barely any hair and full of scabs from itchy mange, she had intestinal worms and also tested positive for heartworm disease. We've introduced her to other dogs her size, both male and female and she gets along great with everyone and easily engages them in play. Her completion of obedience training has improved her confidence and her focus. Frannie will make a great companion to any household with another active dog equal to her energy level.

Brought to the Mesquite Animal Shelter by his owner, Willie had lived his whole life outside on a chain. His condition was extremely poor; he had a huge growth on his neck, was heartworm positive and his spirit was broken.

It took some time, but Willie is finally in great condition, free of heartworms and ready to find his forever home. He does great with other dogs in our kennel and loves to play; in fact, Willie is a dog's dog and missed that camaraderie when he going through heartworm treatment and couldn't run and play like he wanted to. Willie wants to go explore the yard but then he wants to come and be wherever you are - ready to watch the next good movie on Netflex and cuddle on the couch. His new home cannot have cats however. It's Willie's turn to have some joy in his life; got some you can share?

animal.description:
When the Mesquite Shelter filled up, Morpheus' mother Sara was put on the euthanasia list. Thanks to the help of a last minute foster family we saved Sara and quickly determined she was pregnant! Sara's foster family is now her forever home, but Morpheus is still waiting for his.

Morpheus is a gregarious personality in our kennel who loves playing with his sister, Aphrodite, as well as any other dog he meets. He's been on a single home visit and was paralyzed with anxiety at the change in his environment, never having been out of our kennel except to go to adoptions. The potential adopter loved him and wanted to nurture him through that stage, but it was having a negative effect on their senior dog who couldn't relax in the face of Morpheus' anxiety, so he was returned. They stated "He really seeks your affection and he thrives on that attention". So we're looking for someone who can give him some time to relax and feel like he's home. Morpheus will cuddle with a tiny Chihuahua or his sister Aphrodite, he doesn't discriminate on size and would enjoy a canine companion. He graduated from obedience training April 14th 2017 and was a star pupil in his class.

animal.description:
Owen is a sweet calm natured guy, already crate trained and housebroken; he waits his turn to go outside without complaints, but as soon as his business is done he wants to be back inside where you are. He does fine with most dogs, but will not do well with an alpha. His BFF Jax, let Owen be in charge and he preferred that arrangement. He cannot be in a home with cats or small dogs.

Owen was adopted from us in 2015 and we never heard a single complaint about him. In 2019 however, we received a call from the Mesquite Animal Shelter that he'd been turned in there by his adopters as "unable to care for. This is strictly prohibited by our adoption agreement which states ALL adopted pets are returned to us. Once we saw him, we knew why; he was skin and bone, almost 35 pounds underweight, horrible skin condition and heartworm positive. He was turned in with another dog belonging to the family in the same condition and it took months to get them both well enough again to find new homes. Owen is 100% recovered from that treatment and ready for adoption. Owen loves kids and being a family member, he just needs that chance again.

animal.description:
Addie had been with one family since she was a puppy, but as she matured she played too rough with their older dog and small children and developed a high prey instinct for cats. Rather than surrender her to a kill shelter, the owner reached out to us to find her a new home without these elements she didn't meld with.

Losing the only home and family you've ever known is difficult for some dogs and can cause insecurity and a tendency not to trust; this is Addie. She takes time to warm up and get to know you, but when she's reassured of your intent, she's loving, happy and energetic. We'd like to find a mature, cat free/no small children household who'll give Addie time to adjust and become the loving companion she wants to be. Addie has completed basic obedience training and did well in her class; she's eager to please and wants to learn. Her new home should continue that structure as it gives her confidence.

animal.description:
Juneau and her litter mates were born July of 2019.  They were all shy from living in an outside pen with little to no socialization with people but Juneau is the shyest and the only one left of the litter that has not found a home to call her very own.  :(  

Juneau takes time to warm up but once she is comfortable in a home, she is very sweet, loving and very well behaved.  She loves other dogs, is crate trained and potty trained.  Juneau is not a social butterfly and cannot be expected to travel, or be around a lot of people.  Juneau is a home body and comfortable just staying put where she knows she is safe and everything is familiar.  

If you have a heart for the shy dogs and are willing to give this girl a chance, we offer a foster to adopt program to give her time to adjust and settle in and be sure she bonds with her new family.

Fun Facts:

Age (best guess) - 1.5 years
Breed (best guess) - Houndy
Current Weight - 32 lbs
Dog Friendly - Yes
Cat Friendly - Unknown
Kid Friendly - Depends
Potty Trained - Yes
Crate Trained - Yes
Leash Trained - Yes

All of our adult dogs are current on vaccinations, de-wormed, heart worm tested, spayed/neutered, on monthly preventatives & micro chipped prior to adoption. 

*Adoption Fee is $200.00, No out of State Adoptions ,Virtual Home Visits 
 Required  

*We do not require fenced yards for all dogs, fenced yards are required based on a dogs needs. *No invisible fences.

If you would like to meet this dog, please fill out an adoption application at www.unchainedmelodies.org/adopt/

Thank you for adopting!

Dexter loves to play fetch with sticks or balls, he enjoys going on car rides (especially when he can stick his nose into the fresh air!), and he LOVES treats. 

A home with a fenced yard would be ideal, as that allows Dexter to get in some serious ball playing time, which he loves!

Dexter has been around cats and has been curious, but respectful of them. If going to a home with another pet, Dexter would need to be fed separately from other furry friends as he prefers to dine alone. 

Dexter is currently in training working on his leash manners when encountering other dogs, and being able to calm as he can be quick to arouse. His adopter will need to be committed to working on these issues, be patient and give him time to settle into his new environment as he has experienced many transitions recently. Dexter would benefit from a structured routine

We adore this sweet guy, and would love for him to find his forever home. He really is quite sweet- he is a young guy who will thrive in an experienced home where he can get lots of exercise.  Please consider meeting this boy- he is a gorgeous guy, loves people and we would love for him to find his forever home! Please email Janet at astrosped@yahoo.com for more information.

animal.description:
Gregory is a very special boy with an amazing rescue story. He was once known as " The Passaic River Stray," as he lived a lonely life on the streets of Passaic for over a year. All of that changed when we saw his photo online, and worked with a professional trapper to finally bring Gregory to safety.
Once in his foster home, we discovered that Gregory has a goofy, lovey personality with those he loves and trusts. He is understandably shy with strangers and new situations, but warms up quickly once he knows you're a friend. We will continue to work with Gregory to build his confidence, and socialize him with new people.
It is a miracle that Gregory survived for so long on his own. Our wish for Gregory is that he will find a loving, understanding home who will keep him safe and secure, and continue to teach him that he no longer needs to look over his shoulder and be afraid.
Gregory is crate trained, house trained, and walks nicely on a leash.

 
Are you ready to take long walks with this beautiful boy? Submit your application here: https://www.hharteam.org/adoption-form/
Gregory's adoption fee is $200 to a qualified adopter.

animal.description:
Sweet Tess is an 11 year old female with spinal issues. She was surrendered due to changes in her family.

Tess is a beautiful fawn female, about 9-11 years old and owner surrendered when her family could no longer take care of her and her fur siblings. We can truly say Tess picks her human and becomes obsessed with them. She has picked her foster daddy lol. She pines for him when he is not in her line of vision. Her previous owners thought she was paralyzed and carried her around but Tessy walks just fine, especially if Foster Daddy leaves the room, Tessy gets up to follow him. She has either IVDD or DM. Fortunately she is continent of urine and stool and we take her out for frequent potty breaks. Unfortunately, due to being a spinal dog, she has chronic UTI's. She likes toys, sleeping in the big bed next to her person and head scratches. She will defend her food from the other pugs if they get too close, barks at the younger dogs when they get too rowdy and can get quite feisty. She is a special needs pug so probably will not get adopted. But that's ok, we will enjoy her for as long as needed.

animal.description: Roc Man was dropped on the door step late one night of a small town Humane Association in Alabama. This Pitbull boy has been at the shelter for a couple of years now. This small town Humane Association is so clean and well run and very 'humane' and loving to their dogs. They don't give up on them even if it is years that they stay. We know there is someone out there for Roc Man. Just look at this big guy who loves the GIRLS! But we will say he is not a dog that likes to compete with other boy dogs. This stud muffin (who is neutered) is around 6 years old and weighs around 85 lb. When he came to the shelter he was heart worm positive but has been treated him and he is negative and on prevention. Roc Man has had everything done is fully vetted and micro chipped. Roc is a strong guy, typical of the bully breed. In his younger days, Roc was quite a ruff player. Thankfully, we have noticed as he has matured, his playtime is a little more mellow and more respectful of the furniture...lol. Roc proudly shows off his blue ribbon that he won at the Huntsville HOTC Dog Fair for winning "Most Handsome"! We think so too! Please email us if you are interested in this boy! We can transport him northward if you want to adopt him. Please email us at ccrtennessee@gmail.com

animal.description:
Hello my name is Keesha! I am currently part of a loving family of 2 adult humans, a human foster brother and a doggie brother. I am very shy when you meet me but after a couple of days I warm up to people and love cuddles, belly rubs, and attention.  Sometimes I become a 75+ pound lapdog. 

I'm nervous around new people and new experiences, but I warm up after a while.  Not in a bad way, I just get scared and try to walk away or if I see a new person in the driveway I will bark at them to scare them away!  I have not been exposed recently to small children, but I love my teen neighbors next door and meet them at the door when they come over (but my brother gets a little jealous).

I love rabbits and squirrels because they are probably very tasty, I don't know for sure because my family doesn't let me have them, but when I see them I try really hard to get them.

I love playing fetch with balls and sticks and my other toys.  I also love playing tug with my brother and going for walks, with or without my brother, but I pull on the leash. My family and I are working on that though.

I have been doing well with my brother, however I need to be properly introduced to new dogs.  My foster parents waited about a week to decompress me before I met my brother without a barrier.  I just finished up my heartworm treatment at the end of December 2019 and hopefully I will be heartworm free when I am retested in June. 

Overall, I am a fun loving dog that would make a good companion.  I am fairly low maintenance and I believe I would be adaptable to any family environment.
animal.name: Keesha

animal.description:
Bentley is a special boy who needs a special family to love him and take exceptional care of him. He is a lovable goofball and has retained a puppy like demeaner. He loves everyone and everyone who meets him seems to fall in love with him as well. He gets very excited when he meets new people and wants to jump up on them to give hugs and kisses and to receive even more love. Due to this, initially care needs to be taken around children and elderly, as he hasn’t figured out his size. His foster mom has worked with him and he’s improved, learning some self-control until his puppyish qualities get the best of him. He loves playing (albeit roughly) with his foster mom’s cat (who loves rough play) and she usually finds them sleeping next to each other on his bed. He just wants to play whenever he meets another dog although he can be a bit much for the other dog until they get to know each other. When he met a young rottweiler of about 7 months who was more rambunctious than he is, it seemed to scare him some as he seemed to want to back away and avoid the pup. Basically though, this boy loves everyone and everything he encounters.

His foster mom has noticed that he shows way too much interested in running after vehicles. It seems that the larger the vehicle, the more interest he shows. He definitely needs a solidly build fenced in yard so that he can get his energy out but more importantly to keep him safe from his own curiosities. His foster mom has worked with teaching him to restrain himself whenever a vehicle drives past but he would not be a good candidate to be unleashed in an open yard.

Bentley knows basic commands such as: sit, down, stay, drop it, leave it, wait, place. He needs further work on these though as he has difficulty staying still for too long. His foster mom uses ‘leave it’ at each meal before giving him the ok to eat and he’s really good at it, although he may try to sneak in a piece if the command is given right away. He also has not shown any food aggression. He has given the cat a warning growl from time to time but then allows the cat to lick his bowl clean. His foster mom can walk right past him as he eats, touching him in the process without any reaction from him.

Bentley came to SSRR very skinny with some bad stomach problems and had a long history of vomiting as he couldn’t keep his food down. It has been a long, roller coaster journey to get this boy back to health and at a healthy weight. He needs to be kept on a strict raw diet and stay on his medicine to keep him healthy. His diet consists of a variety raw chicken legs and thighs, ground beef, frozen fish (1x a week), steamed sweet potatoes, steamed broccoli, steamed green beans, cottage cheese, and a raw egg (1x a day). His foster mom notes that she has noticed that he absolutely needs to have sweet potatoes every day otherwise his stomach will get upset and he may vomit. She also notes that he prefers them steamed, not willing to eat them raw. Since he’s had such a rough time with his health, he has an absolute love for food and is also a gulper. With this in mind, his foster mom will not give him chicken wings and ensures she’s always right there when he eats any food with bone in it. Everyone must also be sure to be educated not to feed him anything outside of his normal diet as his system is sensitive.

Bentley needs someone special who is dedicated to keep him on a raw diet, meal prep for him, keep him on his medicine and give him all the love and attention this dear boy needs.

animal.description:
Cleo is a 1.5 year old 45 lb lab/terrier mix who is ready and hoping for her forever home.  She is excellent with all people and all dogs she meets!  Her foster home has had many new dogs come and go and she has been excellent with all of them.  

Cleo is extremely affectionate and she loves to snuggle. She loves to play with other dogs and run around the yard. She currently lives with 3 other dogs and does well with all of them.  Cleo loves kids and other dogs but does not do well with cats. She is excellent with the foster puppies in her home and loves to take care of them. 

Her ideal home would have a 6ft fence and another dog for her to play with.  She just really enjoys playtime with her dog friends so we want to make sure she has a friend in her forever home.  

Cleo is crate, leash, and house trained.   Her fosters really think she is quite perfect.  

Cleo is spayed, microchipped, and current on her vaccines.  Her adoption fee is $175.  

If you are interested in adopting her, please fill out an application at FYDRadopt.com and contact us at ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com

animal.description:
Whistler is a very special guy looking for a very special home. He is a typical hound when it comes to sniffing and baying. He loves to use his nose and then tell everyone about it! Whistler is thought to have cerebellar disease which basically means he is missing part of his brain, because of this he often shows some repetitive behaviors. 
Whistler has done great at the sanctuary with a structured routine and relationship building with his caregivers. He can be a sensitive boy and things like loud noises, stormy weather, and constant change can throw him off. He lives with other dogs but prefers to coexist as opposed to constantly play. He really enjoys canine company. He knows how to use his dog door, and it may help in a new home to have a similar set-up to help him with routine. 
Whistler loves walks and cookies and is a good learner with some patience (and cookies). He is also very affectionate and sweet once he knows and trusts you. He loves to bury his soft fur under your arm or weave between your legs for affection. If you're interested in meeting Whistler we ask that you spend some time with him at the sanctuary to make sure it's a good fit. Whistler is a caregiver favorite and his friends would like nothing more than to see him happy in his perfect home.

animal.description:
Ron is an adorable, scruffy guy. Here at the Sanctuary, he gets very excited to go on walks and to the dog park. His most favorite place to go is to Tara's Run, where agility is held. Although he has not officially done the agility course, he does love to jump up on all of the equipment. Ron is a shy dog, so this is a huge accomplishment for him!

We believe Ron would benefit greatly from having another dog in the home as he is very shy and learning how to be social with people. A dog that could help him feel more comfortable and show him the ropes would be beneficial. He will require an understanding home that is okay with Ron not wanting to be physically handled by people and without cats. Once Ron is comfortable with you, he will approach and take treats. He has even started sitting for his treats now! Due to his shyness, we recommend an adult only home.

animal.description:
FOSTER NEEDED! CLASP pay for vet bills, reimburse for foster costs, provide a crate and supplies as well as have dog food delivered to your door by Chewys

Diamond 2 year old, fawn color, Staffordshire Terrier Dog
Requirements: home owner, 6 ft privacy fence, no small children. 

Diamond is a very people-oriented girl. She never runs out of kisses and snuggles. She is also very smart! In training, she picks up on training cues quickly and is very tuned in. She loves to learn and to please! On car rides she does very well. She sits in the passenger seat quietly and enjoys the drive. We do not have any cat or small dog history on her. Generally, she does well with male dogs of her same size (or larger) and same energy level.  However, we are hoping to place her in a home where she can be the only dog and the owner (or foster) would be willing to keep working with Diamond to continually develop her doggy social skills.  Diamond loves to give kisses and jumps to get attention.  We are working on this in training, but even still we do not recommend a home with small children under the age of 10.  A 6ft privacy fence required for adoption. 

MORE PICS IN COMMENTS BELOW

More question? Please email juliawithclasp@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE $200 she is spayed, utd on vaccinations, dewormed, heartworm negative, on heartworm preventions, on flea and tick prevention and she is microchipped.

RESCUE STORY: Diamond was abandoned at a boarding facility by her owner. Several times he called to check on her and said he’d come back, but he never did.

animal.description:
My name is Sheeba (Sheeb)!

I arrived at PATCH Rescue August 9, 2018 after being rescued by an independent rescuer from being dumped in front of a PetSmart. The independent rescuer who has now requested our help to help Sheeb find her furever home!

I was born approximately February 9, 2015

I am approximately 67 pounds

My foster mommie says I am going to make a family VERY happy. I love my walks, attention of humans and am very protective. I would do best as an only fur child and should not be around livestock.

My Adoption fee includes, I have been fixed, up to date on core vaccines (5 in 1, bordetella & rabies), dewormed and microchipped.

If Interested PLEASE contact PATCH Rescue Inc. patchrescue@gmail.com or (760) 706-0728

Adopt a Pet Listings =

https://www.adoptapet.com/adoption_rescue/93645-patch-rescue-inc-victorville-california

PetFinder Listings =

https://www.petfinder.com/member/us/ca/victorville/patch-rescue-inc-ca2487/

Adoption process is verbal interview to determine if we think your family is the right situation for the fur kid you are interested in, application (can be downloaded here: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0B9ZDmKaRLnYfbDZLbDN5Y3hYeWM?usp=sharing), once application is reviewed and approved home check will be performed. Then we say you are becoming part of the PATCH family adopting one of our fur kids, so we expect follow up on our family member throughout their life, i.e. text, email, social media, pictures are our favorite for sharing with the PATCH family!

Please keep in mind we are 100% volunteer run We do not have a facility, completely foster based, so we all have our real jobs, it could take 24 to 48 hours to receive a response.

Thank you for considering adoption to save two lives!

animal.description:
When families break up everyone in the family is affected. We know Raul certainly suffered from a family that went through changes, although we only know half of his story. 

When Raul was found tied up in front of the AALOC kennel it was obvious he had been well cared for: his coat was shiny and smooth, he was well-fed and friendly. A trip to the vet confirmed Raul was healthy. The vet also found a microchip and the AALOC team was able to track down a phone number from one of the previous owners. When contacted the previous owner said one day he came home from work several years ago and his partner was gone with Raul, leaving no information about their whereabouts. He hadn’t heard or seen Raul again. Since then this owner has relocated to Chicago and can no longer care for Raul. So he surrendered Raul to AALOC. We are anxious to find a forever home for Raul but until he is formally adopted we are also looking for a foster family willing to shelter him since we’re sure Raul has only known a loving home in the past.

Based on his physical attributes and personality we believe Raul may be a full-bred American Staffordshire Terrier. Strong, very intelligent and super energetic, Raul is a fun guy looking for a new owner capable of providing him the care and guidance he needs. Raul loves to walk and easily does a mile and a half with our volunteer. Raul also loves to play: one of his favorite games is tug-of-war with his big red rubber ball. Sometimes he even lets you get it for just long enough to throw it out so he can run after it again. He is affectionate and friendly with people and already knows some commands. Raul is sweet-natured and not extremely large, but he is still young and does require consistent discipline and plenty of exercise. In addition, we would not recommend a home with a smaller dog or animal, but Raul may be a good companion for a larger female dog.

Please submit an application to adopt Raul on our website at www.aaloc.org. Once your application is reviewed and approved we will contact you to make an appointment to visit us at AALOC to meet Raul during visiting hours (10am to 3pm daily) and get to know him a bit.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: May be a good companion to a large female dog. Not recommended for households with small dogs or other small animals.

animal.description:
*** BONDED WITH LYN-Z WAY***

Watch their video here!: https://www.facebook.com/TheLimelightPetProject/videos/222207579060431/

NAME: I DARE YOU (named after a song by Shinedown)
AGE/GENDER: DOB 8.7.18, Male
BREED: PITBULL MIX
TEMPERAMENT: Snuggly, playful, stubborn, bouncy, social
WEIGHT: 50ish lbs

HOUSE TRAINING: Good!
CRATE TRAINING: Good! He willingly goes in his crate for his meals and bedtime with a treat.
OTHER DOGS: He does need slow introduction, as he can be very particular about his playmates. He does great with non-dominant and playful dogs. Excitable or dominant dogs are not his jam. He's a bit of a party police, but hey! we don't judge...
CATS: He can ignore them unless they run. Then all's fair in tag...
CHILDREN: Dog-respectful children, 8 and older. The boy has springs for feet and can parkour off little people.
ADOPTION DONATION: $800 (for both Dare and Lyn-Z)
HEALTH: DARE was born with a cleft palate. After months of hand feeding, he had his surgery and it was successful. However, his mouth needs to be continuously monitored and consideration given to his selection of toys and diet. He has a sensitive stomach and has some food allergies. No chicken! He also has environmental allergies and is on Cytopoint injections every other month. Dare is neutered, microchipped, flea treated, and dewormed.

HISTORY: Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to take in Dare and his family (his mother and brothers who have since been adopted) when they were relinquished to animal control.

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: Dare is an extremely outgoing little guy with people. He doesn't feel he has any enemies. He has no clue about stranger danger and loves meeting new people. He will definitely invite robbers into your home and offer them lattes along with your silverware. However, he's a little standoffish with dogs initially since he wants to be the boss of everybody and is not a dog who can go to dog parks or doggie daycare, as he has some bulldog stubbornness and dominance. Can we say party police unless he's the one throwing the party.

He is an energetic little guy but tires easily, having little heat intolerance and low stamina, most likely due to his cleft palate situation. He says it's because of his cleft palate, I say he has to embrace his bulldog genes and their physical limitations. He will definitely not be a jogging buddy and long strenuous hikes would be out of the question, as well as walks in hotter temperatures. He loves to be outside, however, and is great for walks when the weather is milder. I would say he's an easy-going 3-miler trail buddy.

He's quite content to play with his dog friends or amuse himself in the backyard. He prefers females and non-dominant dogs. He does need some time when doing dog introductions as he can be initially prickly. But he listens very well to corrections as long as the other dog is easygoing. He's not tolerant with dogs with "issues" because he's a hypocrite that way... so judgy. He's an overall goofy guy with a zest for life. He's the happiest little boy and very quick with his affection. He loves to cuddle and kiss, and kiss, and kiss... sooooo much kissing and so much bouncing. He will make out with anyone who is able and willing and if you're lying in bed, then you are fair game to cuddle and kiss.

Dare loves Lyn-Z and is her seeing eye dog. He's also her ESA when she is nervous and scared. He likes to give her kisses, too. They cuddle, they play, they sleep together, share toys, share people. They both enjoy leisurely walks along the beach at sunset.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and either a Martingale collar or a harness, depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO:
Motley Zoo Animal Rescue is a volunteer run, foster based, 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization based in Redmond, WA. Motley Zoo does not have a traditional shelter location, but instead, utilizes private foster homes which care for the animals individually, in a home environment, until a "furever" home is found.

Motley Zoo also runs "Rock Star Treatment" Dog Daycare & Training Studio in Redmond, WA which is a day-use facility and does not hold kennels of adoptable animals. The dogs there are owned animals who come to the facility while their families are at work and school so they can play and socialize in a safe environment. We dub this service our "Year-round" fundraising program which helps us support our rescue animals and the $15,000/ month vet bills we incur. This Studio location does have an Adoptable Cat Lounge, where cats may live until adoption, which is the exception to any aforementioned rules.

Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application so we can get you started on the journey to finding a new, furry friend! Once you have been approved to adopt, then we can set up a meeting with the animal you have been matched with.

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

animal.description:
** OUR SHELTER IS CURRENTLY CLOSED TO THE PUBLIC AND WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. THIS MAY CHANGE AND WE MAY BE UNABLE TO UPDATE, SO IF YOUR CALL ISN'T RETURNED WITHIN 2 BUSINESS DAYS, WE MAY HAVE CLOSED TO THE PUBLIC COMPLETELY IN AN EFFORT TO KEEP OURSELVES AND OUR OWN FAMILIES HEALTHY. WE WILL STILL CARE FOR THE DOGS DURING THESE UNCERTAIN TIME. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Janice. I'm about 7 years old and I weigh about 65 lbs. 
I was found as a stray in the Wellsville area and I was brought in to the pound. 
I am a very sweet, energetic, playful girl looking for a loving family to join. 
I am very clean in my kennel at night and I appear to have maybe been a house dog at some point. 
I get along with some, but not all other dogs, so I should meet any dogs that I would live with before I get adopted.
If you're looking for a sweet dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me. 

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE. 

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt. 

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter. 

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am. 
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance. 
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend. 

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable. 

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663 
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

animal.description:
Beautiful Lulu... she is smart, energetic, active and will be your loyal new best friend. Lulu came to us after her family couldn't keep her through no fault of her own. Shelter life has been very stressful for Lulu and she still hasn't completely settled in, despite being with us for several months.

Lulu needs an owner who has had Malinois experience. She needs consistency, mental stimulation, and tons of exercise. Lulu is very high strung and if she is not getting the activity she needs, she will make it known. Lulu has gone through training sessions and we expect any potential adopter to follow through with consistent training. Lulu does well in play groups with other dogs, but would be best as the only child due to some food guarding. Lulu also needs an adult only home with not a lot of people coming and going and no small children or teens, and preferably in a single family home/condo with a yard (no apartments!).

With all that said, Lulu really is a great girl who will make someone very happy. She can't wait to find her future confident best friend who she can be loyal, protective and make smile. If you're interested in learning more about Lulu, please send us an email or give us a call.

*Please complete our online application for further consideration. We do best fit for both dog and family, and completing an application is not a guarantee of approval.

animal.description:
Zeke is a beautiful bridled Beagle/Pit/Boxer/Hound mix. He is full of energy and kisses! Zeke will need long walks and/or an area to run around and get his energy out. He is a little shy when brought into the house, but I'm sure would get use to it. He is a slow, deliberate eater, which has caused him to miss out on a lot of treats that his siblings gobble down.

Zeke's shots are up to date. He has been treated for worms and fleas as needed.

Zeke has a high prey drive and should not be placed in a home with small lose "prey" type animals. He will chase them and attempt to catch them. So far Zeke has shown to be submissive with other dogs. He is loyal to his "pack" and will follow the Alpha.

animal.description:
Arrow is 6 year old 55lb uniquely beautiful mix of Terrier-Labrador-Husky-Shepherd. She is intelligent, eager to please, and ready to learn. She loves hiking, is great on a leash and one of the best companions you could ask for. She is crate and potty trained. 

Arrow will only be adopted to a home with NO children and NO other animals. 

Arrow has had a history of being strongly vocally afraid when meeting new people which she is working through in her current foster home with a professional trainer. Arrow requires an adopter that is willing to work with our trainer during her adoption process. 
Our trainer will help to implement her structured yet humble training that she has been taught into their lives with her for a smooth transition. 
Arrow is a one of a kind of dog that will need someone who is willing to learn her training and help teach her that she has a person or family that is in charge and will take care of her, so she doesn’t have to feel the need to protect herself anymore. 
She thrives off of knowing who is in charge, what are the rules, and what her role is. If you are that person that is willing to give this beautiful dog a chance and learn some fun training along the way than please apply to meet beautiful Arrow

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This poor little guy is Pablo and he is a bully mix that was born around 5/20/18 and now weighs about 60 pounds. He has had a rough life already but we hope those days are forever behind him. You can tell from his photos that he suffered greatly with an embedded collar and a cable tie stuck around him that slashed up his neck so severely, it looked like someone tried to decapitate him. Pablo walked up to a local business on Palafox at the perfect time because a good samaritan saw him and knew he needed immediate help. Pablo's neck wounds have been treated by our vet and he is healed. On top of the neck injury, Pablo was so overrun with fleas and parasites that most of his hair was missing. Despite the trauma and pain he was obviously suffering from, Pablo is a very sweet and friendly boy. Pablo must have an expierenced, prevoius bully breed handler due to his resources guarding on food and toys. These issues could be addressed with proper training from the right person.

Amazing Grace Bully Rescue is a foster based rescue in the Pensacola, Florida area. We do not have a physical building. If you would like to meet any of our pups, the first step is to fill out our online application so we can contact you.

Our adoption fee for Pablo is $150 and includes his neuter, current shots, rabies vaccine, and a registered microchip.

If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

If you have any questions, please text your question to 723-2037. You may also send a message to our Amazing Grace Bully Rescue Page on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, or send an email directly to amazinggracebullyrescue@gmail.com

Disclaimer: We are located in the Pensacola, Florida area and will consider local applicants first, especially with puppies since we use a vet in the local area.

animal.description: Wed like you to meet this handsome pit bull mix named Angelo. When he came into the shelter about 6 months ago, he had heartworms, a disease transmitted by mosquitos, which is easily prevented by giving your dog a monthly pill. His previous owner did not bother to do this. Fortunately a volunteer paid for the expensive heartworm treatment so that he could be cured. Now all healthy, he is actively looking for a forever home. Because of his muscular build and serious expression, Angelo can appear a bit intimidating in his kennel. But as soon as he sees someone he knows coming to take him out, our boy gets all happy and wiggley and his friendly personality emerges. In the play yard, he chases after his toys and then joyfully runs over to greet his person and wait for cuddles and ear rubs. He also likes to go for leash walks, but is strong and needs to learn loose leash walking. Since he loves food treats, training shouldnt be very difficult for a patient, consistent owner. When we introduced Angelo to another dog he did very well, so if you have a dog, bring it in for a meet and greet. (Dont forget your rabies certificate!) Angelo is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and all ready to move into your home and your heart. Angelo. He can come off as a bit loud and intimidating but dont let that scare you off. Once this handsome fella gets to know you and warms up to you, hes a great dog and companion. Meet our handsome pit bull mix named Angelo. When Angelo came into the shelter he was heartworm positive, a disease transmitted by misquitos. A volunteer paid for his heartworm treatment so that he could be cured. Now that Angelo has beat his heartworm disease he is actively seeking his forever home with a loving family who can give him all the attention this sweet boy deserves. When in the play yard he chases after his toys and joyfully runs over to greet his person for cuddles and belly rubs. Angelo loves to be center of attention and show off his awesome tricks such as sit and give paw. He loves his treats unconditionally and will do commands just to get them! Angelo has alot of love to give, once you become his person you have a life time friend in him. Angelo is notorious for his smile that will light up the room!

animal.description: This is Bolt and we know that this boy definitely needs an experienced adult household, with no kids under 16, and an above ground fenced yard (no apartments). We think Bolt is about 2ish and he is also said to be pretty laid but but as you can see from the pictures, he is not very healthy right now, and we need time to see his real self come out. He has an ear issue that GRRAND is getting him treatment for as well, and this could be an ongoing issue for a bit. Bolt is crate trained and is looking for a home that has another stable dog in the house. He is very dog selective but we have found that the more stable of a dog he is with, the happier he is! animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Rocky is waiting for someone very special. He is a wonderful companion but needs to learn to trust you and will need someone who is patient and understanding. But, once he knows you love him and are a good person, he will shower you with his love.

Rocky loves to be by your side. He wants to sit on the couch with you and expects to sleep in bed with you. He will even help with laundry or enjoy a morning cup of coffee with you. You will always find him at your feet under the dinner table at dinner time. He gets excited about his morning and evening walks and is a great running companion. Rocky can easily run three miles and is just that motivation you need sometimes from a running partner. Rocky has been on road trips to the mountains and swimming in the rivers. He loves to go on hikes and play with his toys in the yard. Rocky has his blankets he drags around the house and finds his perfect spot on the chair to gaze out the window.

Rocky lives with 5 cats and is pretty good with them, although he is occasionally interested and will playful run after them. Once he gets a swipe to the face he backs off. He lives with an alpha lab. Rocky does like to play and will get a bit wild with other dogs but my lab knows how to handle him and will put him in his place. He is gets uneasy when other dogs pass during walks and will need constant coaching and reassurance that he is safe. Treats work well for this and he has been working on this for a long time. He will do well with continuous reinforcement.

Rocky will do best in a home with a yard, where he won't be home for long periods of time alone, where he gets plenty of exercise and adventure, where he will be part of the family and get lots of attention. He is uneasy around young children and will do best in a quiet household with adults or adults with older children (over 16) who know how to handle dogs well.

Rocky is a true love bug and we want to find that perfect family for him. We know you are out there.

He is getting a refresher on household manners and potty training in his foster home, and he hasn't had an accident yet. He knows his basic commands and is a really well behaved boy. He does best in a house rather than an apartment, as the noises all around him make him nervous when no one is home with him.
